00:06:09.920 --> 00:06:12.140
He did write poems
and they're fantastic.

00:06:12.140 --> 00:06:15.210
He was a tank commander in
World War I, and obviously goes

00:06:15.210 --> 00:06:17.960
on to World War II to
much greater acclaim.

00:06:17.960 --> 00:06:20.720
The second thing is the
issue of citizenship.

00:06:20.720 --> 00:06:23.890
World War I really comes to define,
or begins to define what it means

00:06:23.890 --> 00:06:28.000
to be a modern citizen in the
U.S. What do I owe the government?

00:06:28.000 --> 00:06:29.770
What does the government owe me?

00:06:29.770 --> 00:06:31.490
And part of that is conscription.

00:06:31.490 --> 00:06:35.920
You know, we did have a conscripted
army in the Civil War, but only 8%.

00:06:35.920 --> 00:06:38.380
World War I, 72% of the
army is conscripted.

00:06:38.380 --> 00:06:41.510
And the idea of conscription itself
was something people had to reckon

00:06:41.510 --> 00:06:43.110
with in terms of what it
meant for liberties, right?

00:06:43.110 --> 00:06:46.900
And that brings us to the issue of
civil liberties and civil rights,

00:06:46.900 --> 00:06:50.990
which are kind of dovetailed
within this idea of citizenship

00:06:50.990 --> 00:06:52.580
and idea of conscription.

00:06:52.580 --> 00:06:55.550
On the one hand you have the
creation of Civil Liberties Bureau,

00:06:55.550 --> 00:06:59.650 position:56%
which will become famously the ACLU,
and you have the famous court cases,

00:06:59.650 --> 00:07:01.980
these are just two, there are
others, Schenck versus U.S.,

00:07:01.980 --> 00:07:04.580
Abrams versus U.S., where Justice
Holmes goes from -- in the --

00:07:04.580 --> 00:07:08.950 position:56%
