Wilson's files, which in

00:11:47.780 --> 00:11:52.340
and of itself could require, you
know, a lifetime of expertise.

00:11:52.340 --> 00:11:57.620
But really, the American
people are in your debt.

00:11:57.620 --> 00:12:00.460
American democracy is in your debt.

00:12:00.460 --> 00:12:03.220
It's not just people
who care about history,

00:12:03.220 --> 00:12:08.580 position:56%
but policymaking is based upon
ideas and assumptions about history.

00:12:08.580 --> 00:12:11.730
Politics are informed by history.

00:12:11.730 --> 00:12:14.800
Legal developments are
informed by history.

00:12:14.800 --> 00:12:18.620
And so the work that you
do is this foundation

00:12:18.620 --> 00:12:20.720
that helps enable everything else.

00:12:20.720 --> 00:12:24.160
So I feel privileged
to have an opportunity

00:12:24.160 --> 00:12:25.980
to thank you for that today.

00:12:25.980 --> 00:12:31.280
I also thank everybody else who,
it's kind of an exciting day

00:12:31.280 --> 00:12:35.960 position:56%
in Washington, and I'm just so
happy that you either needed a break

00:12:35.960 --> 00:12:39.570
from it or something
and decided to come.

00:12:39.570 --> 00:12:41.720
We really have a wonderful panel.

00:12:41.720 --> 00:12:45.000 position:56%
All I want to do right now is just
to try to set the stage a little bit

00:12:45.000 --> 00:12:48.160
and maybe ask a couple
of sort of questions,

00:12:48.160 --> 00:12:51.750
not for them to deal with,
but for us to think about.

00:12:51.750 --> 00:12:57.030
So let's go back to April of 1917.

00:12:57.030 --> 00:13:01.400
You know, first let me sort of
step back, 1916 election was one

00:13:01.400 --> 00:13:04.450
of those elections so
close Woodrow Wilson went

00:13:04.450 --> 00:13:07.160 position:56%
to bed having been told he had lost.

00:13:07.160 --> 00:13:08.920
Only gets up in the morning to find

00:13:08.920 --> 00:13:11.150
that Charles Evans Hughes
had lost the election

00:13:11.150 --> 00:13:12.450
and Wilson got reelected.

00:13:12.450 --> 00:13:16.390
That was the election where
the Democratic Party ran

00:13:16.390 --> 00:13:19.910
on the slogan, he kept
us out of war.

00:13:19.910 --> 00:13:25.530
And my opinion, the best work on
the 1916 election says that, yes,

00:13:25.530 --> 00:13:29.450
war issues carried
Wilson over the top.

00:13:29.450 --> 00:13:33.950
It was that concern about war, not
just in Europe but also with Mexico

00:13:33.950 --> 00:13:38.750
that led to key votes for Wilson
in the west and in the mid-west.

00:13:38.750 --> 00:13:43.910
So an antiwar perspective
helps decide the election,

00:13:43.910 --> 00:13:49.110
then how do we get to April
1917 and Wilson goes to Congress

00:13:49.110 --> 00:13:50.990
and asks for war declaration.

00:13:50.990 --> 00:13:55.200
After Wilson himself goes
through this torturous turn

00:13:55.200 --> 00:13:58.340
that his biographer's call
Wilson's Gethsemane, you know,

00:13:58.340 --> 00:14:02.190
where Jesus prayed the night
before his death and his sweat was

00:14:02.190 --> 00:14:04.240
like drops of blood
falling on the ground.

00:14:04.240 --> 00:14:06.430
I mean, it really --
read his letters.

00:14:06.430 --> 00:14:10.400
And he says to a friend,
my thought is under seize.

00:14:10.400 --> 00:14:13.710
Even you don't understand
how difficult it is.

00:14:13.710 --> 00:14:15.130
So what happened?

00:14:15.130 --> 00:14:18.130
Well, lots of things
happened, but a crucial thing

00:14:18.130 --> 00:14:23.950 position:56%
that happens is Germany starts
doing unrestricted submarine warfare

00:14:23.950 --> 00:14:30.010
in the Atlantic announced
January 31, you know, February 1

00:14:30.010 --> 00:14:31.720
and then ships are being sunk.

00:14:31.720 --> 00:14:34.920
Now there had been submarine
warfare in the Atlantic.

00:14:34.920 --> 00:14:37.110
There had just been a deal
with the U.S. We're not going

00:14:37.110 --> 00:14:38.680
to go after neutral shipping.

00:14:38.680 --> 00:14:42.690
Germany says, nope,
everybody's fair game.

00:14:42.690 --> 00:14:47.500 position:56%
And the New York Times had on the
front page the ships that went down,

00:14:47.500 --> 00:14:52.980
how many casualties, everybody
is watching it day by day.

00:14:52.980 --> 00:14:56.890
The -- and basically the
casualties, you know, step up.

00:14:56.890 --> 00:14:59.580
There's more to say about
this than I will right now,

00:14:59.580 --> 00:15:07.690
but it's in this moment when
Wilson, little by little,

00:15:07.690 --> 00:15:12.640
sort of comes to the idea
that the only response is

00:15:12.640 --> 00:15:15.730
to turn towards war.

00:15:15.730 --> 00:15:19.560
Now, Wilson in asking
for a declaration

00:15:19.560 --> 00:15:21.010
of war he basically says,

00:15:21.010 --> 00:15:26.130
in this context neutrality
is no longer feasible.

00:15:26.130 --> 00:15:30.000
Germany, he said, was
at war with all nations.

00:15:30.000 --> 00:15:32.940
So what was the U.S.
doing in going to war?

00:15:32.940 --> 00:15:38.210
Our object now is to vindicate the
principles of peace and justice

00:15:38.210 --> 00:15:39.800
and [inaudible] of the world

00:15:39.800 --> 00:15:43.930
as against selfish
and autocratic power.

00:15:43.930 --> 00:15:46.830
And probably the most
famous line is,

00:15:46.830 --> 00:15:50.170
the world must be made
safe for democracy.

00:15:50.170 --> 00:15:52.800
Now to accomplish U.S.
objectives in this war,

00:15:52.800 --> 00:15:55.040
what did the United
States need to do?

00:15:55.040 --> 00:15:56.340
Two things.

00:15:56.340 --> 00:16:01.080
All resources of government
had to be devoted to the war.

00:16:01.080 --> 00:16:02.380
All resources.

00:16:02.380 --> 00:16:05.390
And that's a typical
thing presidents call for.

00:16:05.390 --> 00:16:11.070
He also demanded that the people
themselves be devoted to war.

00:16:11.070 --> 00:16:15.560
He said in his speech, if there
should be disloyalty it will be

00:16:15.560 --> 00:16:19.460
dealt with with a firm
hand of stern repression.

00:16:19.460 --> 00:16:21.020
It's sort of a shocking sentence.

00:16:21.020 --> 00:16:25.110
It will be dealt with with a
firm hand of stern repression.

00:16:25.110 --> 00:16:28.170
He had been talking about
German Americans, but he says,

00:16:28.170 --> 00:16:32.050
most of them, they're loyal.

00:16:32.050 --> 00:16:35.950
But among German Americans and
others, the problems would come

00:16:35.950 --> 00:16:39.880
from what he called a
lawless and malignant view.

00:16:39.880 --> 00:16:44.280
So dissenters, you see,
are lawless and malignant.

00:16:44.280 --> 00:16:47.140
They're sort of a cancer
on the [inaudible].

00:16:47.140 --> 00:16:49.760
As his speech taught -- sought --

00:16:49.760 --> 00:16:53.990
so as his speech sought to unite
Americans behind a grand purpose,

00:16:53.990 --> 00:16:57.440
he helped to lay the basis
for the marginalization

00:16:57.440 --> 00:16:59.720
and criminalization of dissent.

00:16:59.720 --> 00:17:05.870 position:56%
In this way, even as he upheld
democracy as this global aspiration,

00:17:05.870 --> 00:17:10.860
he endangered a central bedrock
of democracy of free people,

00:17:10.860 --> 00:17:15.090
free to speak politically and free
to criticize their government.

00:17:15.090 --> 00:17:18.590
It's the -- it's the protection
of dissent that is a sort

00:17:18.590 --> 00:17:22.210
of a central aspect of
having a free government.

00:17:22.210 --> 00:17:26.700
Now when we gauge how well
American institutions have stood

00:17:26.700 --> 00:17:31.060
up to the pressures during wars,
generally American scholars,

00:17:31.060 --> 00:17:34.330
especially clinical scientists
and [inaudible] tend to sort

00:17:34.330 --> 00:17:36.940
of compare wars against each other.

00:17:36.940 --> 00:17:40.680
Let's think about one president's
war power as compared to another,

00:17:40.680 --> 00:17:43.140
and the Civil War gets
a lot of play in this.

00:17:43.140 --> 00:17:46.500
And Lincoln's suspension of
the writ of habeas corpus

00:17:46.500 --> 00:17:49.120
in the Civil War is a prime example

00:17:49.120 --> 00:17:52.690
of presidents essentially
overrunning constitutional limits

00:17:52.690 --> 00:17:53.990
during war.

00:17:53.990 --> 00:17:56.870
Sometimes it's used as a way of
-- you know, it always happens.

00:17:56.870 --> 00:17:58.400
Don't worry so much.

00:17:58.400 --> 00:18:00.640 position:56%
It'll all go back to normal someday.

00:18:00.640 --> 00:18:03.050 position:56%
Okay, so when we think about that --

00:18:03.050 --> 00:18:06.190
these examples, what
kinds of pres --

00:18:06.190 --> 00:18:13.560
which kinds of presidential actions
are justifiable, and the context

00:18:13.560 --> 00:18:16.180
of these decisions matters a lot?

00:18:16.180 --> 00:18:21.860
So Lincoln's 1861 suspension of
the writ of habeas corpus came

00:18:21.860 --> 00:18:26.260
when Confederate sympathizers
threatened supply lines

00:18:26.260 --> 00:18:29.620
through Maryland to the
District of Columbia.

00:18:29.620 --> 00:18:35.190
The Civil War, as a whole, of
course, obviously happened here.

00:18:35.190 --> 00:18:37.350
It happened here.

00:18:37.350 --> 00:18:42.680
And so Lincoln is acting to protect
the ability of the government

00:18:42.680 --> 00:18:46.780
to function to get food and
other supplies into Washington,

00:18:46.780 --> 00:18:51.860
D.C. Compare this with 1917.

00:18:51.860 --> 00:18:55.560 position:56%
Now the war was happening elsewhere.

00:18:55.560 --> 00:18:59.440
It wasn't happening within
the territorial U.S. at all.

00:18:59.440 --> 00:19:01.880
American supply lines,
were they threatened?

00:19:01.880 --> 00:19:05.600
Well, the ability of American
companies to ship goods overseas

00:19:05.600 --> 00:19:07.720
and the United States
companies were trading

00:19:07.720 --> 00:19:10.720
with everybody to ship
goods overseas.

00:19:10.720 --> 00:19:15.630
That was cut off and there was
ships backed up in the harbors.

00:19:15.630 --> 00:19:20.760
And ship companies were, after
Woodrow Wilson saying, what --

00:19:20.760 --> 00:19:24.970
you got to do something,
because we can't sail anywhere.

00:19:29.040 --> 00:19:31.370
There was also a threat
to American lives.

00:19:31.370 --> 00:19:33.020
And at one point Lincoln says,

00:19:33.020 --> 00:19:36.200
if Germany does anything
we're going to do something.

00:19:36.200 --> 00:19:39.370
And he didn't really say what.

00:19:39.370 --> 00:19:43.230 position:56%
And he didn't say what the something
was that would generate more action,

00:19:43.230 --> 00:19:49.180
but it caused the world to focus on
Wilson and to watch every sinking.

00:19:49.180 --> 00:19:54.720
First death was a working
man about three days

00:19:54.720 --> 00:19:56.510
after the German announcement,

00:19:56.510 --> 00:19:59.840
African American merchant
sailor killed

00:19:59.840 --> 00:20:02.460
on I believe it was a British ship.

00:20:02.460 --> 00:20:08.810
And that wasn't the act that would
drive Wilson to call for a war.

00:20:08.810 --> 00:20:12.000
But these deaths sort of
started to accumulate.

00:20:12.000 --> 00:20:16.690 position:56%
So the Americans who were threatened
were people who worked on ships.

00:20:16.690 --> 00:20:18.400
They were ship captains,

00:20:18.400 --> 00:20:23.630
and probably the largest number was
basically working-class laborers

00:20:23.630 --> 00:20:28.280
who worked in the boiler room,
including many men of color.

00:20:28.280 --> 00:20:32.720 position:56%
And then there was another
category, Americans who freely chose

00:20:32.720 --> 00:20:38.670
to travel, often to sail on
fancy British ocean liners,

00:20:38.670 --> 00:20:42.950
ocean liners that had contraband
in the hole and were armed.

00:20:42.950 --> 00:20:45.570
In other words, they are warships.

00:20:45.570 --> 00:20:48.730
They are fair targets.

00:20:48.730 --> 00:20:51.030
The --

00:20:54.040 --> 00:20:59.620
And the deaths that then sort
of motivate the press coverage

00:20:59.620 --> 00:21:03.500 position:56%
and the emotional tenor of
American politics, it's actually not

00:21:03.500 --> 00:21:09.810
about the working men, it's
about the society ladies

00:21:09.810 --> 00:21:14.430
and wealthy travelers choosing
to make a trip across a war zone

00:21:14.430 --> 00:21:18.840
on ships that are fair
targets, and that's the overact

00:21:18.840 --> 00:21:22.500
that basically helped shift the,
again, the sort of emotional tenor

00:21:22.500 --> 00:21:27.020
of American politics
at this point in time.

00:21:27.020 --> 00:21:29.770
But -- and then when the U.S.
enters the war, what does it do?

00:21:29.770 --> 00:21:32.300
Let's protect the oceans.

00:21:32.300 --> 00:21:34.940
Let's have safe lanes
for American ships.

00:21:34.940 --> 00:21:38.190
It sounds like we need
to have a naval war

00:21:38.190 --> 00:21:40.750
to protect American
interests in the Atlantic.

00:21:40.750 --> 00:21:44.550
Well, instead, the U.S. jumps
all the way in and, of course,

00:21:44.550 --> 00:21:49.060 position:56%
Wilson in part has his broader goals
for the world community in mind,

00:21:49.060 --> 00:21:52.920
wanting to be at the table in
Paris at the end of the war.

00:21:52.920 --> 00:21:58.180
That's achieved by sending
American troops to Europe.

00:21:58.180 --> 00:22:04.130
American shipping in the Atlantic
might well have been managed

00:22:04.130 --> 00:22:07.440 position:56%
through a narrower U.S. involvement.

00:22:07.440 --> 00:22:11.480
So there's lots of interesting
questions about how the U.S. got

00:22:11.480 --> 00:22:14.330
to where it got to with
this sort of full engagement

00:22:14.330 --> 00:22:16.950
for a limited period
of time in World War I.

00:22:16.950 --> 00:22:22.510
Now, when we think about World
War I and the suppression

00:22:22.510 --> 00:22:27.150
of civil liberties, we need to keep
in mind, I think, that this isn't

00:22:27.150 --> 00:22:29.960
like Lincoln's experience.

00:22:29.960 --> 00:22:34.330 position:56%
And when we have a war somewhere
else that's then producing this sort

00:22:34.330 --> 00:22:37.580
of domestic political
environment, where does that come

00:22:37.580 --> 00:22:39.200
from and what's driving it?

00:22:39.200 --> 00:22:43.480 position:56%
It's not just war per se happens
and then there's a reaction at home.

00:22:43.480 --> 00:22:46.040
And the sort of best work I
think in political science

00:22:46.040 --> 00:22:49.190
about public reactions to
war says it's not actually --

00:22:49.190 --> 00:22:53.710
it's not war per se that does
it, it's the way war gets talked

00:22:53.710 --> 00:22:56.860
about in elite discourse
and partisan politics.

00:22:56.860 --> 00:22:58.910
So it's basically a
domestic political

00:22:58.910 --> 00:23:03.750
and social phenomenon that's
driving the domestic reaction.

00:23:03.750 --> 00:23:06.280
At least that's an argument.

00:23:06.280 --> 00:23:10.960
The legacy of World War I, which is
tremendously important in the law

00:23:10.960 --> 00:23:18.010
and policy community, the
legacy is -- matters so much.

00:23:18.010 --> 00:23:22.260 position:56%
Eventually we get this growth of
this law of civil liberties and a --

00:23:22.260 --> 00:23:25.650
and a flourishing civil
liberties tradition in spite

00:23:25.650 --> 00:23:30.760
of its coexistence with
continuing forms of oppression,

00:23:30.760 --> 00:23:35.010
including race discrimination
and segregation.

00:23:35.010 --> 00:23:39.940
On these issues there are many
productive points of disagreement,

00:23:39.940 --> 00:23:43.530
or at least difference
among our speakers today,

00:23:43.530 --> 00:23:47.260
on whether the federal government
helped or hindered the development

00:23:47.260 --> 00:23:51.720
of civil liberties on the role of
social movements and organizations,

00:23:51.720 --> 00:23:56.140
like the NAACP and the ACLU
on the history of ideas,

00:23:56.140 --> 00:23:58.960
a tremendously important
and rich area of study,

00:23:58.960 --> 00:24:02.250
and on the role of the course.

00:24:02.250 --> 00:24:04.580
And so with that, I'd
like to turn this

00:24:04.580 --> 00:24:07.880
over to Geoff Stone
to get us started.

00:24:11.510 --> 00:24:14.500
[ Applause ]

00:24:17.040 --> 00:24:18.340
&gt;&gt; Geoffrey Stone: Thanks.

00:24:18.340 --> 00:24:20.420
I want to talk a bit about
the issues of free speech,

00:24:20.420 --> 00:24:23.870
free press during World War I.

00:24:23.870 --> 00:24:27.840
During the First World War there
were more than 2000 prosecutions

00:24:27.840 --> 00:24:31.420
of individuals for criticizing
the war or the draft.

00:24:31.420 --> 00:24:35.410
Sentences of those ranged
up to 20 years in prison.

00:24:35.410 --> 00:24:38.920
Any person who had the audacity
to make such statements,

00:24:38.920 --> 00:24:42.740
whether in a speech, in a book,
in a newspaper, or in a pamphlet,

00:24:42.740 --> 00:24:45.840
were subject to prosecution
and conviction.

00:24:45.840 --> 00:24:49.580 position:56%
Those prosecuted included
journalists, politicians, activists,

00:24:49.580 --> 00:24:53.460 position:56%
members of the clergy, and
ordinary citizens across the nation.

00:24:53.460 --> 00:24:55.940
They even included Eugene
Debs, who had received more

00:24:55.940 --> 00:25:00.320
than a million votes for
president in the 1912 election.

00:25:00.320 --> 00:25:02.130
The vast majority of
these convictions were

00:25:02.130 --> 00:25:05.700
for violating the Espionage
Act of 1917.

00:25:05.700 --> 00:25:10.370
Now, the Espionage Act of 1917
was directed primarily at acts

00:25:10.370 --> 00:25:15.350
of espionage and acts directed at
the protection of military secrets.

00:25:15.350 --> 00:25:19.180
But section three of the act also
made it a crime for any person to,

00:25:19.180 --> 00:25:24.210 position:56%
quote, cause or attempt to cause
insubordination, disloyalty, mutiny,

00:25:24.210 --> 00:25:28.290
or refusal of duty in the military
services of the United State,

00:25:28.290 --> 00:25:30.210
or to willfully obstruct or --

00:25:30.210 --> 00:25:34.630
the recruiting and enlistment
service of the United States.

00:25:34.630 --> 00:25:37.540
Now on its face, that
provision would not seem

00:25:37.540 --> 00:25:40.750
to forbid newspaper
articles, speeches, pamphlets,

00:25:40.750 --> 00:25:45.160 position:56%
and the like that did nothing more
than criticize the war or the draft.

00:25:45.160 --> 00:25:48.840
But the federal courts, with but
a few exceptions, interpreted

00:25:48.840 --> 00:25:52.530
and applied the Act as making
it crime for any person

00:25:52.530 --> 00:25:55.410
to make any statement that
might have even a tendency

00:25:55.410 --> 00:25:58.260
to turn people against the war.

00:25:58.260 --> 00:26:01.260
Because of that interpretation,
any criticism of the war

00:26:01.260 --> 00:26:04.140
or the draft was deemed
unlawful resulting

00:26:04.140 --> 00:26:08.950 position:56%
in the most aggressively speech
suppressive era in American history.

00:26:08.950 --> 00:26:11.540
Now, those who were prosecuted
under the Espionage Act

00:26:11.540 --> 00:26:15.510
for their speech tended to raise
one of two, or both, objections.

00:26:15.510 --> 00:26:20.500
First, that the Act should not be
interpreted to reach the speech

00:26:20.500 --> 00:26:21.800
in which they had engaged.

00:26:21.800 --> 00:26:25.160
And second, and if the Act were
interpreted to reach the speech

00:26:25.160 --> 00:26:29.510
with which they engaged it
violated the First Amendment.

00:26:29.510 --> 00:26:31.940
Both objections were, with
only a few exceptions,

00:26:31.940 --> 00:26:34.330 position:56%
emphatically rejected by the courts,

00:26:34.330 --> 00:26:37.280
including the Supreme
Court of the United States.

00:26:37.280 --> 00:26:40.520
I'd like to focus in my
few minutes on the question

00:26:40.520 --> 00:26:42.500 position:56%
of the meaning of the Espionage Act.

00:26:42.500 --> 00:26:44.040
And I'm sure we'll have
an opportunity to talk

00:26:44.040 --> 00:26:45.900
about the First Amendment
issues later.

00:26:45.900 --> 00:26:49.780
So in the months leading up
to the United States entry

00:26:49.780 --> 00:26:54.840
into World War I, there was fierce
opposition to that possibility.

00:26:54.840 --> 00:26:58.290
The American people were
divided about the war.

00:26:58.290 --> 00:27:00.870
Many Americans did not
understand what the war

00:27:00.870 --> 00:27:04.030
in Europe was all about, and
many of them had no desire

00:27:04.030 --> 00:27:06.020
to send their sons off to die

00:27:06.020 --> 00:27:09.560
in what seemed a senseless
and brutal conflict.

00:27:09.560 --> 00:27:12.070
Many thought, in short, that
the United States had no dog

00:27:12.070 --> 00:27:15.140
in this fight, and that the best
course for the nation was simply

00:27:15.140 --> 00:27:19.560 position:56%
to stand aside and let the Europeans
fight it out among themselves.

00:27:19.560 --> 00:27:22.790
President Woodrow Wilson,
though, who, as you heard,

00:27:22.790 --> 00:27:26.860
had been elected -- reelected
president in 1916 on the platform

00:27:26.860 --> 00:27:29.990
that he had kept us out
of war, had other ideas.

00:27:29.990 --> 00:27:33.570
And by early 1917 he had come
to the conclusion that our entry

00:27:33.570 --> 00:27:35.730
into the war was inevitable.

00:27:35.730 --> 00:27:39.360
But Wilson understood he
faced a serious dilemma.

00:27:39.360 --> 00:27:42.400
And that dilemma was the
lack of public support.

00:27:42.400 --> 00:27:44.300
It's difficult to fight
a war successfully

00:27:44.300 --> 00:27:47.130
if you do not have the
support of your people.

00:27:47.130 --> 00:27:51.770 position:56%
To address the widespread opposition
to our entry into the war, Wilson;

00:27:51.770 --> 00:27:54.210
therefore, launched
two types of programs.

00:27:54.210 --> 00:27:57.090
The first, called the Community
for Public Information,

00:27:57.090 --> 00:28:00.140
was a propaganda program
run out of the White House.

00:28:00.140 --> 00:28:05.260
It was essentially designed with
the task of demonizing the enemy

00:28:05.260 --> 00:28:08.170
across the nation and
whipping up a war fervor

00:28:08.170 --> 00:28:13.820
by basically having editorials and
speeches and pamphlets and posters

00:28:13.820 --> 00:28:17.120
that showed how horrible the
enemy was and how essential it was

00:28:17.120 --> 00:28:20.660
to American freedom
to fight in this war.

00:28:20.660 --> 00:28:23.850
But Wilson understood that
wouldn't be sufficient to deal

00:28:23.850 --> 00:28:26.390
with the dissent that was
going on in the country.

00:28:26.390 --> 00:28:28.060
And he; therefore,
needed legislation

00:28:28.060 --> 00:28:29.840
that would silence that dissent.

00:28:29.840 --> 00:28:33.680
Now, the United States government
had not enacted federal legislation

00:28:33.680 --> 00:28:37.100
making it a crime to criticize the
government of the United States

00:28:37.100 --> 00:28:39.920
since the Sedition Act of 1798,

00:28:39.920 --> 00:28:42.910
an episode that had been
roundly condemned over the course

00:28:42.910 --> 00:28:44.930
of the following century.

00:28:44.930 --> 00:28:47.760
Indeed having learned the
painful lessons of that history,

00:28:47.760 --> 00:28:50.830
the United States had intentionally
refrained from enacting

00:28:50.830 --> 00:28:54.450
such legislation during the war
of 1812, during the Civil War,

00:28:54.450 --> 00:28:56.780 position:56%
and during the Spanish American War.

00:28:56.780 --> 00:29:01.370 position:56%
Nonetheless, in lead up to our entry
into World War I, Wilson decided

00:29:01.370 --> 00:29:03.730
that aggressive legislation
was necessary

00:29:03.730 --> 00:29:06.120
to stifle criticism of his war.

00:29:06.120 --> 00:29:09.870
Thus, Wilson called upon Congress
to enact legislation, quote,

00:29:09.870 --> 00:29:12.150
to suppress disloyal activities.

00:29:12.150 --> 00:29:15.620
The Department of Justice proposed
to Congress the initial version

00:29:15.620 --> 00:29:19.580
of Espionage Act, which included
a provision declaring it unlawful

00:29:19.580 --> 00:29:24.570
for any person in time of war
to publish any information

00:29:24.570 --> 00:29:28.450 position:56%
that the president, in his judgment,
deemed to be of such character

00:29:28.450 --> 00:29:31.220
that it might be harmful to
the interests of the nation.

00:29:31.220 --> 00:29:35.010
This proposal triggered
a firestorm of protest.

00:29:35.010 --> 00:29:38.300
The American Newspaper Association
declared that the provision, quote,

00:29:38.300 --> 00:29:42.010 position:56%
strikes at the fundamental rights of
the American people, and newspapers

00:29:42.010 --> 00:29:45.600
across the land condemned it as
oppression as a glaring attempt

00:29:45.600 --> 00:29:48.610
to muzzle free speech, and as an
effort to suppress the freedom

00:29:48.610 --> 00:29:52.320
of the press and the freedom people
of the to express on its judgments

00:29:52.320 --> 00:29:54.600
on the acts of public servants.

00:29:54.600 --> 00:29:57.830
Members of Congress from both
parties similarly condemned the

00:29:57.830 --> 00:29:59.290
proposed legislation.

00:29:59.290 --> 00:30:02.690
Senator Johnson of California, for
example, charged that the, quote,

00:30:02.690 --> 00:30:06.000
preservation of free speech
is of transcendent importance,

00:30:06.000 --> 00:30:08.180
especially in times
of national stress.

00:30:08.180 --> 00:30:11.630
And Representative Madden of
Illinois protested that, quote,

00:30:11.630 --> 00:30:14.630
while you're fighting to establish
the democracy of the world,

00:30:14.630 --> 00:30:16.690
we ought not to do the very thing

00:30:16.690 --> 00:30:20.410
that will establish
autocracy in America.

00:30:20.410 --> 00:30:23.940
Although Wilson then made a
direct appeal to Congress arguing

00:30:23.940 --> 00:30:26.780
that such authority, quote,
is absolutely necessary

00:30:26.780 --> 00:30:30.460
to the public safety, Congress
nonetheless defeated the proposed

00:30:30.460 --> 00:30:33.600
legislation by an overwhelming
majority.

00:30:33.600 --> 00:30:38.720
Thereafter, Congress enacted what
became the Espionage Act of 1917,

00:30:38.720 --> 00:30:41.370
with its much more
narrowly focused provisions

00:30:41.370 --> 00:30:43.910
which were directed
specifically at speech intended

00:30:43.910 --> 00:30:47.110
to cause insubordination
in the military

00:30:47.110 --> 00:30:49.360
or to cause obstruction
of the draft.

00:30:49.360 --> 00:30:55.260
As enacted, this legislation was
not designed as a broadside attack

00:30:55.260 --> 00:30:56.670
on all criticism of the war,

00:30:56.670 --> 00:31:00.240
but it's a carefully considered
enactment designed to deal

00:31:00.240 --> 00:31:03.110
with very specific
military concerns.

00:31:03.110 --> 00:31:07.200
Wilson's attorney general, Charles
Gregory, was bitterly disappointed,

00:31:07.200 --> 00:31:09.600
complaining that Congress
had taken the teeth

00:31:09.600 --> 00:31:13.330
out of the legislation
we attempted to enact.

00:31:13.330 --> 00:31:17.010
Nonetheless, with the advent of the
war federal judges across the land,

00:31:17.010 --> 00:31:19.600
acting at the insistence and
encouragement of the Department

00:31:19.600 --> 00:31:21.650
of Justice and of the
Executive Branch,

00:31:21.650 --> 00:31:24.760
interpreted these provisions
very broadly.

00:31:24.760 --> 00:31:28.690
Basically they held that any
speech that criticized the war

00:31:28.690 --> 00:31:31.980
and the draft could have
the tendency to turn people

00:31:31.980 --> 00:31:34.850
against the war and;
therefore, could lead people

00:31:34.850 --> 00:31:37.630
to refuse induction into
the military and could lead

00:31:37.630 --> 00:31:41.160
to insubordination on the part
of individuals in the military.

00:31:41.160 --> 00:31:42.630
And; therefore, it
had a bad tendency

00:31:42.630 --> 00:31:44.870
which would cause these effects.

00:31:44.870 --> 00:31:48.580
But said, the defendants, the
statute talks about intent

00:31:48.580 --> 00:31:49.880
to cause content obstruction,

00:31:49.880 --> 00:31:52.280
intent to cause insubordination,
that wasn't our intent.

00:31:52.280 --> 00:31:55.160
Our intent was to criticize
the war and the draft.

00:31:55.160 --> 00:31:57.200
The court said, doesn't matter.

00:31:57.200 --> 00:31:59.050
You're held to have
intended the natural

00:31:59.050 --> 00:32:01.800
and foreseeable consequences
of your speech.

00:32:01.800 --> 00:32:03.200
And since this was
one of the natural

00:32:03.200 --> 00:32:07.410
and foreseeable consequences you
can be punished under the statute.

00:32:07.410 --> 00:32:10.190
Only a few judges resisted.

00:32:10.190 --> 00:32:13.900
The most famous of these,
Learned Hand in the Masses case,

00:32:13.900 --> 00:32:17.870
wrote a memorable opinion in which
held that in light of the history

00:32:17.870 --> 00:32:21.870
of free speech on issues of
war in the United States,

00:32:21.870 --> 00:32:24.770
and legislative history
in the Congress,

00:32:24.770 --> 00:32:28.310
that he would interpret the
Espionage Act as applying only

00:32:28.310 --> 00:32:32.750
to speech that expressly
incited obstruction of the draft

00:32:32.750 --> 00:32:36.380
or insubordination in the military,
and that speech that stops short

00:32:36.380 --> 00:32:39.250
of expressly encouraging
people who refuse induction

00:32:39.250 --> 00:32:40.800
or expressly encouraging them

00:32:40.800 --> 00:32:44.650
to be insubordinate was
not prohibited by the Act.

00:32:44.650 --> 00:32:46.780
That was short lived, however.

00:32:46.780 --> 00:32:50.370
His opinion in Masses was promptly
overruled by the Court of Appeals,

00:32:50.370 --> 00:32:52.750
and Hand himself was punished.

00:32:52.750 --> 00:32:56.620
He had been awaiting a promotion to
the Court of Appeals that was put

00:32:56.620 --> 00:32:59.890
in abeyance and he remained on the
District Court for another decade,

00:32:59.890 --> 00:33:03.070
in part as punishment
for his opinion.

00:33:03.070 --> 00:33:07.200
Indeed a year later, in 1918,
now in the heat of war fever,

00:33:07.200 --> 00:33:10.040
Congress enacted the
Sedition Act of 1918,

00:33:10.040 --> 00:33:12.860
which finally gave the Wilson
administration what it had wanted

00:33:12.860 --> 00:33:14.160
all along.

00:33:14.160 --> 00:33:17.360
The Sedition Act made it a crime,
among other things, quote, to utter

00:33:17.360 --> 00:33:21.890
or to publish any disloyal language
intended to cause contempt or scorn

00:33:21.890 --> 00:33:24.460
for the government of the
United States, the Constitution,

00:33:24.460 --> 00:33:27.720
or the flag, or to utter any
language opposing the cause

00:33:27.720 --> 00:33:30.140 position:56%
of the United States in time of war.

00:33:30.140 --> 00:33:34.510
The Sedition Act of 1918
was repealed in 1921,

00:33:34.510 --> 00:33:37.730
but the Espionage Act of
1917 remains on the books.

00:33:37.730 --> 00:33:39.530
Thank you.

00:33:39.530 --> 00:33:43.500
[ Applause ]

00:33:56.250 --> 00:33:57.550
&gt;&gt; Jeremy Kessler: I want to stress

00:33:57.550 --> 00:34:02.120
in my brief opening comments
the extensive resistance

00:34:02.120 --> 00:34:06.490
to free speech claims during World
War I, especially from the courts,

00:34:06.490 --> 00:34:11.400 position:56%
as Geoff has already mentioned, but
also, and more surprisingly I think,

00:34:11.400 --> 00:34:16.180
for many progressive
intellectuals as well.

00:34:16.180 --> 00:34:20.610
As Geoff mentioned,
the judicial resistance

00:34:20.610 --> 00:34:24.250
to free speech claims
was most obvious

00:34:24.250 --> 00:34:30.590
in cases construing the
federal Espionage Act of 1917.

00:34:30.590 --> 00:34:35.450
I think it's worth repeating the
three main provisions of that act.

00:34:35.450 --> 00:34:41.050 position:56%
One is publishing false reports with
intent to injure the war effort.

00:34:41.050 --> 00:34:43.040
Second, causing or attempting

00:34:43.040 --> 00:34:46.590
to cause insubordination
in the Armed Forces.

00:34:46.590 --> 00:34:51.890
And third, willfully obstructing
recruitment into the Armed Forces.

00:34:51.890 --> 00:34:56.640 position:56%
And, as Geoff mentioned, convictions
could lead to fines of up to $10,000

00:34:56.640 --> 00:34:59.320
and 20 years imprisonment.

00:35:01.040 --> 00:35:05.200
Government prosecutions under
the Espionage Act overwhelmingly

00:35:05.200 --> 00:35:10.580
resulted in convictions, and judges
overwhelmingly rejected claims

00:35:10.580 --> 00:35:12.970
by defendants that to be convicted

00:35:12.970 --> 00:35:18.810
for antiwar speech violated their
First Amendment free speech rights.

00:35:18.810 --> 00:35:26.110 position:56%
The most typical kind of speech that
led to a conviction was speech often

00:35:26.110 --> 00:35:28.320
by socialists or members
of the industrial workers

00:35:28.320 --> 00:35:31.710
of the world claiming that
the financial interests

00:35:31.710 --> 00:35:35.810
of capitalists were
primarily responsible

00:35:35.810 --> 00:35:40.150 position:56%
for the American entry into the war.

00:35:40.150 --> 00:35:44.670
And many juries and
judges construed that kind

00:35:44.670 --> 00:35:47.350
of opposition to war as false.

00:35:47.350 --> 00:35:50.470
That's not what Congress
said in declaring war.

00:35:50.470 --> 00:35:55.280
And also that that antiwar
speech had a tendency

00:35:55.280 --> 00:36:00.030
to cause insubordination
and obstruct recruitment.

00:36:00.030 --> 00:36:03.900
Much milder speech also
led to convictions.

00:36:03.900 --> 00:36:08.920
This is an extreme case, but
not the only extreme case.

00:36:08.920 --> 00:36:13.060
A minister was found guilty
of causing insubordination

00:36:13.060 --> 00:36:18.020
under the Espionage Act because
he distributed a pamphlet teaching

00:36:18.020 --> 00:36:20.990
that Christians should
not kill during wars.

00:36:20.990 --> 00:36:24.620
And that was held to have a
tendency to cause the obstruction

00:36:24.620 --> 00:36:28.090
of recruitment and insubordination.

00:36:28.090 --> 00:36:31.970
There were some rare acquittals
under Espionage Act prosecutions,

00:36:31.970 --> 00:36:36.790 position:56%
but as Geoff mentioned, many of
them were reversed by higher courts.

00:36:36.790 --> 00:36:40.440
And one of these rare
acquittals prompted Congress

00:36:40.440 --> 00:36:44.690
to amend the Espionage Act to
make convictions even easier

00:36:44.690 --> 00:36:47.910
than they already were,
which is very easy.

00:36:47.910 --> 00:36:52.590 position:56%
And I think it's worth telling you
a little bit about the case that led

00:36:52.590 --> 00:36:56.070
to the passage of the Sedition Act.

00:36:56.070 --> 00:37:01.130
A judge in Montana directed
acquittal of a defendant.

00:37:01.130 --> 00:37:05.490
The judge pointed out that the
defendant's antiwar statements,

00:37:05.490 --> 00:37:10.390
anti-capitalist statements,
occurred at picnics

00:37:10.390 --> 00:37:16.290
and during saloon argument
at a small village in Montana

00:37:16.290 --> 00:37:21.490
that was 60 miles from the nearest
train station and 100's of miles

00:37:21.490 --> 00:37:24.850
from the nearest military base.

00:37:24.850 --> 00:37:29.270
And according to the judge,
that is not enough evidence

00:37:29.270 --> 00:37:32.970
to show an intent to
cause insubordination.

00:37:32.970 --> 00:37:39.310
The Attorney General of the United
States cited this rare acquittal

00:37:39.310 --> 00:37:42.990
as evidence of the ineffectiveness
of the Espionage Act,

00:37:42.990 --> 00:37:45.880
which overwhelmingly
led to convictions.

00:37:45.880 --> 00:37:49.640
And the Attorney General
successfully urged Congress

00:37:49.640 --> 00:37:54.610
to pass the Sedition Act of
1918, which as Geoff said,

00:37:54.610 --> 00:38:01.980 position:56%
expressly prohibited, quote unquote,
unpatriotic or disloyal language.

00:38:01.980 --> 00:38:08.570
Now, this widespread
hostility to free speech claims

00:38:08.570 --> 00:38:15.310
under the Espionage Act extended
to the United States Supreme Court.

00:38:15.310 --> 00:38:17.070
The first Supreme Court decisions,

00:38:17.070 --> 00:38:20.680
as many of you probably
know, were in March 1919.

00:38:20.680 --> 00:38:23.640
All three were unanimous decisions.

00:38:23.640 --> 00:38:28.370
All three were written by Justice
Holmes, who still had a reputation

00:38:28.370 --> 00:38:33.940
as a progressive hero
when I was in law school.

00:38:33.940 --> 00:38:40.510
Most public attention was focused
on the case of Eugene Debs,

00:38:40.510 --> 00:38:45.790
who was by far the most famous
defendant in an Espionage Act case.

00:38:45.790 --> 00:38:49.000
As many of you know, I'm sure
Debs was a major union leader

00:38:49.000 --> 00:38:50.300
in the United States.

00:38:50.300 --> 00:38:52.470
He had been a recent
Socialist party candidate

00:38:52.470 --> 00:38:54.280
for president of United States.

00:38:54.280 --> 00:38:56.910
I think he got more votes
as a percentage basis

00:38:56.910 --> 00:38:58.360
until Ross Perot, is that?

00:38:58.360 --> 00:39:02.260
He was a major candidate.

00:39:02.260 --> 00:39:04.970
Holmes observed that the speech

00:39:04.970 --> 00:39:09.360
for which Debs had been convicted
consisted of restatements

00:39:09.360 --> 00:39:13.810
of socialist opposition to war,
and also praise of socialists

00:39:13.810 --> 00:39:15.840
who had already been convicted

00:39:15.840 --> 00:39:20.680
for violating the draft
law and the Espionage Act.

00:39:20.680 --> 00:39:25.230
And Holmes concluded that the jury
was justified in finding that kind

00:39:25.230 --> 00:39:28.770
of speech, having a tendency

00:39:28.770 --> 00:39:31.730
to obstruct the recruitment
service and; therefore,

00:39:31.730 --> 00:39:34.860
the conviction of Debs was upheld.

00:39:34.860 --> 00:39:42.630
Notice again the use of tendency to
justify the punishment of speech.

00:39:42.630 --> 00:39:48.260
Holmes relied on the bad tendency
of speech in upholding convictions

00:39:48.260 --> 00:39:52.050
in the two companion cases,
called Schenck and [inaudible].

00:39:52.050 --> 00:39:54.490
And it's interesting, many of you
probably have heard the term clear

00:39:54.490 --> 00:39:56.870
and present danger
from the Schenck case,

00:39:56.870 --> 00:39:58.400
which for decades was considered

00:39:58.400 --> 00:40:00.970
to be a protective interpretation
of the First Amendment.

00:40:00.970 --> 00:40:04.790
Holmes did not even use that
phrase in the other two cases,

00:40:04.790 --> 00:40:09.100
yet he relied on the bad tendency
of speech to uphold convictions

00:40:09.100 --> 00:40:14.630
under the Espionage Act for
opposition to American involvement

00:40:14.630 --> 00:40:19.250
in World War I, basically the claim
it was a capitalists' war rejecting

00:40:19.250 --> 00:40:21.760
First Amendment claims.

00:40:22.820 --> 00:40:27.680
Now, I want to emphasize that
this reliance on the bad tendency

00:40:27.680 --> 00:40:30.920
of speech to justify convictions

00:40:30.920 --> 00:40:36.730 position:56%
and to deny First Amendment claims
was not new under the Espionage Act.

00:40:36.730 --> 00:40:41.370
This was the standard approach
to rejecting free speech claims

00:40:41.370 --> 00:40:44.740
of all kinds throughout
the United States,

00:40:44.740 --> 00:40:47.110
throughout the entire
judicial system,

00:40:47.110 --> 00:40:50.600
from the Civil War
until World War I.

00:40:50.600 --> 00:40:53.420
And I want to give you
an example of the use

00:40:53.420 --> 00:40:56.010
of the bad tendency
approach before the war,

00:40:56.010 --> 00:40:58.830
and this is by Holmes
himself in a case

00:40:58.830 --> 00:41:03.420
in 1907 called Patterson
versus Colorado.

00:41:03.420 --> 00:41:06.790
Okay, Patterson, Thomas
Patterson was a Democratic senator

00:41:06.790 --> 00:41:08.930
from Colorado who was
also the publisher

00:41:08.930 --> 00:41:11.590
of a leading newspaper in Colorado.

00:41:11.590 --> 00:41:14.740
The newspaper published
editorials, cartoons,

00:41:14.740 --> 00:41:19.020
articles criticizing
the Republican majority

00:41:19.020 --> 00:41:22.680
of the Colorado Supreme
Court for acting as tools

00:41:22.680 --> 00:41:26.330 position:56%
of the wealthy utility corporations.

00:41:26.330 --> 00:41:29.240
And prodded by the
Colorado Supreme Court,

00:41:29.240 --> 00:41:32.490
the Colorado Attorney
General brought contempt

00:41:32.490 --> 00:41:36.540
of court proceedings
against Senator Patterson,

00:41:36.540 --> 00:41:40.950
and the Republican majority of
the Colorado Supreme Court upheld

00:41:40.950 --> 00:41:43.970
that conviction for
contempt of court.

00:41:43.970 --> 00:41:46.960
Patterson appealed to the United
States Supreme Court claiming the

00:41:46.960 --> 00:41:50.810 position:56%
conviction violated his First
Amendment rights and asserting truth

00:41:50.810 --> 00:41:54.610
as a defense, a basic defense
under the First Amendment.

00:41:54.610 --> 00:41:57.390
Holmes, writing for eight
of the nine justices,

00:41:57.390 --> 00:42:00.540
rejected the First Amendment claim.

00:42:00.540 --> 00:42:01.950
Reasoning?

00:42:01.950 --> 00:42:07.890
Publications criticizing judicial
behavior in pending cases tend

00:42:07.890 --> 00:42:11.200
to obstruct the administration
of justice, whether

00:42:11.200 --> 00:42:16.560
or not the allegations are true,
First Amendment claim denied.

00:42:16.560 --> 00:42:22.030
And this reliance on the tendency
of speech could be found in 100's

00:42:22.030 --> 00:42:25.110
of cases throughout the
American judicial system

00:42:25.110 --> 00:42:28.160
between the Civil War
and World War I.

00:42:28.160 --> 00:42:32.320
I find it very interesting
that a man named Gilbert Roe,

00:42:32.320 --> 00:42:35.610
who had been a lawyer
for many defendants

00:42:35.610 --> 00:42:39.200
in free speech cases
before World War I,

00:42:39.200 --> 00:42:43.700
testified in the Congressional
hearings about the espionage bill

00:42:43.700 --> 00:42:49.000
and warned about the potential
use of the bad tendency approach.

00:42:49.000 --> 00:42:50.630
He says, I know about this danger

00:42:50.630 --> 00:42:53.690
because I handled free
speech cases before the war.

00:42:53.690 --> 00:42:56.190
He didn't object of
a falsity clause,

00:42:56.190 --> 00:43:00.710
but he did correctly
presciently predict

00:43:00.710 --> 00:43:06.620
that the courts would construe
unpopular antiwar speech

00:43:06.620 --> 00:43:11.110
as having a tendency
to obstruct recruitment

00:43:11.110 --> 00:43:16.290
and cause insubordination, and
he turned out to be right based

00:43:16.290 --> 00:43:18.170
on the judicial decisions.

00:43:18.170 --> 00:43:26.380
So very briefly in closing I want
to emphasize that this resistance

00:43:26.380 --> 00:43:32.300
to free speech claims during World
War I was not limited to judges.

00:43:32.300 --> 00:43:33.870
It was surprising to me to find

00:43:33.870 --> 00:43:36.760
out that leading progressive
intellectuals

00:43:36.760 --> 00:43:42.280
in the United States had at best
ambivalent views about free speech.

00:43:42.280 --> 00:43:44.320
Now some of this explicable.

00:43:44.320 --> 00:43:51.420
The progressives identified
constitutional rights

00:43:51.420 --> 00:43:57.900 position:56%
with excessive individualism, and
they attributed many of the problems

00:43:57.900 --> 00:44:05.070
in early 20th century America,
such as destructive inequality,

00:44:05.070 --> 00:44:10.740
division throughout society, to the
over emphasis on individual rights,

00:44:10.740 --> 00:44:13.290
including individual
constitutional rights.

00:44:13.290 --> 00:44:17.420
Now they focused on the individual
rights of property and liberty

00:44:17.420 --> 00:44:20.020
of contract, which
as many of you know,

00:44:20.020 --> 00:44:25.290
were used to invalidate
progressive reform legislation,

00:44:25.290 --> 00:44:28.130
but they weren't sympathetic
to other expressions

00:44:28.130 --> 00:44:33.300
of individual rights, including
those based on the First Amendment.

00:44:33.300 --> 00:44:38.580
Also, the progressives
placed great emphasis

00:44:38.580 --> 00:44:41.240
on achieving social harmony.

00:44:41.240 --> 00:44:44.160
That was a key element
of progressive thought.

00:44:44.160 --> 00:44:49.410
And that attention to harmony
limited their conception

00:44:49.410 --> 00:44:51.010
of free speech.

00:44:51.010 --> 00:44:57.090
Yes, free speech that contributes
to social reconstruction is good

00:44:57.090 --> 00:45:00.500
and should be protected,
but free speech

00:45:00.500 --> 00:45:04.880
that expresses the
inevitability of class conflict,

00:45:04.880 --> 00:45:08.810
or that denies the feasibility,

00:45:08.810 --> 00:45:12.830
possibility of ultimate social
unity, that was not good speech,

00:45:12.830 --> 00:45:15.800
and they did not really
believe in protecting it.

00:45:15.800 --> 00:45:20.470
And a great example of this
progressive view is John Dewey,

00:45:20.470 --> 00:45:23.800
perhaps the leading progressive
intellectual, public intellectual

00:45:23.800 --> 00:45:27.300
in the country at the time,
probably more sympathetic

00:45:27.300 --> 00:45:31.710
to free speech claims than most
progressives, yet in an article

00:45:31.710 --> 00:45:33.650
in the New Republic Magazine soon

00:45:33.650 --> 00:45:38.520
after the United States
entered World War I in 1917,

00:45:38.520 --> 00:45:43.580
Dewey criticized pacifist
opposition to the war as a failure

00:45:43.580 --> 00:45:46.390
to seize its Democratic
possibilities,

00:45:46.390 --> 00:45:52.240
and he ridiculed dissenters
for invoking, quote unquote,

00:45:52.240 --> 00:45:57.410
early Victorian platitudes about
the sanctity of individual rights.

00:45:57.410 --> 00:45:59.570
That's John Dewey, a progressive.

00:45:59.570 --> 00:46:03.790
So I'll stop here with
that, and I look forward

00:46:03.790 --> 00:46:06.820
to the other presentations and to
the discussion that will follow.

00:46:06.820 --> 00:46:08.620
Thanks.

