00:49:42.090 --> 00:49:43.390
and depose something interesting.

00:49:43.390 --> 00:49:46.720
I mean, for me it was focusing
on the development of the NAACP,

00:49:46.720 --> 00:49:49.690
and then to realize
that actually they begin

00:49:49.690 --> 00:49:54.900
and they grow very much during
the time of World War I.

00:49:54.900 --> 00:49:58.550
So the NAACP was founded in 190

00:49:58.550 --> 00:50:01.050
around this issue of
racial violence.

00:50:01.050 --> 00:50:05.690
This big race massacre happened
in Springfield, Illinois.

00:50:05.690 --> 00:50:11.040
And a lot of really concerned white
abolitionists became, what is this?

00:50:11.040 --> 00:50:14.060
Why is there this white
violence outside of the south?

00:50:14.060 --> 00:50:17.310
We should organize and we
should do something, right?

00:50:17.310 --> 00:50:20.270
And so then what happens
between 1909

00:50:20.270 --> 00:50:25.340
and 1911 is they form what
then becomes the NAACP.

00:50:25.340 --> 00:50:28.330
At the time, I know many people
in here do also know this,

00:50:28.330 --> 00:50:30.770
the board was all white with
one black member, which is going

00:50:30.770 --> 00:50:32.180
to be W. E. B. Dubois, right?

00:50:32.180 --> 00:50:34.320
He's going to be a single
black member on the board

00:50:34.320 --> 00:50:36.130
of directors at the NAACP.

00:50:36.130 --> 00:50:38.930
And the big issue that they
take up, I don't ever talk

00:50:38.930 --> 00:50:42.860
about the NAACP also without
talking about Ida B. Wells.

00:50:42.860 --> 00:50:46.330
So, and I'm going to say one
very quick thing about that.

00:50:46.330 --> 00:50:49.030
So the big issue they take up is
this issue around racial violence,

00:50:49.030 --> 00:50:50.970
in part because of
Ida B. Wells' work

00:50:50.970 --> 00:50:54.180
around the anti-lynching
crusades at the end of the 19th,

00:50:54.180 --> 00:50:56.340
in the beginning of
the 20th century.

00:50:56.340 --> 00:50:58.450
She makes the case very clear

00:50:58.450 --> 00:51:02.320 position:56%
that African Americans cannot
actually be free until they are free

00:51:02.320 --> 00:51:04.100
from the threat of racial violence,

00:51:04.100 --> 00:51:06.310
meaning lynching and
mob violence, right?

00:51:06.310 --> 00:51:09.340
And so the beginning planning
meetings of the NAACP,

00:51:09.340 --> 00:51:12.800
Ida B. Wells is around, but Dubois,
because of serious gender issues

00:51:12.800 --> 00:51:15.720
that he actually has, then
pushes her to the side,

00:51:15.720 --> 00:51:17.270
but they still do take
up this issue, right?

00:51:17.270 --> 00:51:19.510
Like, history is fun because
all these characters are

00:51:19.510 --> 00:51:21.830
so much more complex
than I think sometimes

00:51:21.830 --> 00:51:23.130
that at least media
gives them credit for.

00:51:23.130 --> 00:51:25.360
All right, so the NAACP is formed.

00:51:25.360 --> 00:51:28.570
And they go after,
they very much believe

00:51:28.570 --> 00:51:31.650
that this is the way towards
freedom in this country.

00:51:31.650 --> 00:51:37.200
Sometimes in order to kind of
try to bring home the importance

00:51:37.200 --> 00:51:39.610
of racial violence to
the early development

00:51:39.610 --> 00:51:43.510
of the NAACP I often use this
one quote that, when I read it,

00:51:43.510 --> 00:51:45.230
I just had to kind of
sit back because it --

00:51:45.230 --> 00:51:48.220
and it had to sit with
me for a while.

00:51:48.220 --> 00:51:51.400
So at this board meeting in
1916, Mary White Ovington,

00:51:51.400 --> 00:51:53.610
a white board member,
is a bit confused

00:51:53.610 --> 00:51:57.780
about why the NAACP is not going
after other important areas

00:51:57.780 --> 00:52:01.170
that we now associate with
civil rights, such as education,

00:52:01.170 --> 00:52:03.240
voting, and housing segregation.

00:52:03.240 --> 00:52:07.430
And one of the black leaders,
he's now the board of directors

00:52:07.430 --> 00:52:10.780
at the NAACP, turns to her
and he says, all the Amer --

00:52:10.780 --> 00:52:13.770
and this is a quote, all the
American Negro wants is a chance

00:52:13.770 --> 00:52:16.490
to live without a rope
around his neck, end quote.

00:52:16.490 --> 00:52:19.650
Right? So the point here
is that before we can fight

00:52:19.650 --> 00:52:22.250
for the other rights, before we
can enjoy these other rights,

00:52:22.250 --> 00:52:25.460
that African Americans actually
first have to live first.

00:52:25.460 --> 00:52:29.280
And so this is a statement in 1916,

00:52:29.280 --> 00:52:33.040 position:56%
despite what I told you very quickly
earlier that the NAACP was formed

00:52:33.040 --> 00:52:35.800
and it was kind of this all
white board of directors

00:52:35.800 --> 00:52:39.690
with Dubois, that changes in 1916.

00:52:39.690 --> 00:52:43.560 position:56%
James Wood Johnson comes on board
and assumes leadership of the NAACP,

00:52:43.560 --> 00:52:45.960
and Walter White, not from
Breaking Bad, but Walter White

00:52:45.960 --> 00:52:49.600
of NAACP fame, comes on in 1917.

00:52:49.600 --> 00:52:52.680
And they then resurrect the
membership and it expands.

00:52:52.680 --> 00:52:54.860
They're like, why is
all the membership

00:52:54.860 --> 00:52:56.630
in the mid-west and the north?

00:52:56.630 --> 00:53:01.030
Like, there is clearly African
Americans, and a lot of them

00:53:01.030 --> 00:53:04.630
in the south, and we need to
organize and mobilize and set

00:53:04.630 --> 00:53:08.160
up chapters in the
south immediately.

00:53:08.160 --> 00:53:10.640
And so you see the numbers
in terms of the membership

00:53:10.640 --> 00:53:16.890
of the NAACP changing
dramatically between 1916 and 1919,

00:53:16.890 --> 00:53:21.240
in part because of the leadership
of Johnson and White at the NAACP.

00:53:21.240 --> 00:53:23.620
So the way they go about this
issue of racial violence,

00:53:23.620 --> 00:53:27.230
and with my five minutes left
I'm going to condense a lot here,

00:53:27.230 --> 00:53:28.530
is they believe that the first --

00:53:28.530 --> 00:53:31.730
and this is one of the things that
I've struggled with and I still do,

00:53:31.730 --> 00:53:35.450
before there was such a
notion of civil rights, right,

00:53:35.450 --> 00:53:37.720
we today if I say civil rights
you'll be like, all right,

00:53:37.720 --> 00:53:41.560
march in Washington [inaudible],
it's like, things come to mind.

00:53:41.560 --> 00:53:43.740
But this is like, again,
the early part of the NAACP,

00:53:43.740 --> 00:53:45.770
the federal government
has not come out, right,

00:53:45.770 --> 00:53:48.490
to consistently protect
African American rights.

00:53:48.490 --> 00:53:51.010 position:56%
So they're fighting for civil rights
before there's like this notion

00:53:51.010 --> 00:53:53.860 position:56%
of what civil rights actually means.

00:53:53.860 --> 00:53:56.260
And so they believe, all
right, first what we're going

00:53:56.260 --> 00:53:58.410
to do is we're going to launch
this public opinion campaign.

00:53:58.410 --> 00:54:00.690
We're going to organize
people in the streets.

00:54:00.690 --> 00:54:04.270
And if we can just reach the
hearts and minds of Americans,

00:54:04.270 --> 00:54:06.280
and then things will change, right?

00:54:06.280 --> 00:54:09.350
Like white America
will realize the terror

00:54:09.350 --> 00:54:12.410
of racial violence and
it will stop, right?

00:54:12.410 --> 00:54:16.770
So they do this and they
organize, and significant inroads,

00:54:16.770 --> 00:54:18.090
but it doesn't stop, right?

00:54:18.090 --> 00:54:22.390
So then they were like, all right,
we have to attack formal politics.

00:54:22.390 --> 00:54:24.380
So with that -- and the
three branches, right?

00:54:24.380 --> 00:54:27.850
So one, obviously, they
do this whole campaign

00:54:27.850 --> 00:54:30.990
for anti-lynching legislation
inside of Congress

00:54:30.990 --> 00:54:33.890
and they make far -- they get far.

00:54:33.890 --> 00:54:37.610
And then a Supreme Court case
around criminal procedure,

00:54:37.610 --> 00:54:40.760
around basically the
legal lynching, the --

00:54:40.760 --> 00:54:44.910
kind of the sentencing to die of 12
African American men in Arkansas.

00:54:44.910 --> 00:54:49.110
And the point that I want to
focus on here though that I --

00:54:49.110 --> 00:54:52.580
that I found fascinating is the
work inside the executive, right?

00:54:52.580 --> 00:54:57.080
So here's the NAACP, this
incredibly outsider organization.

00:54:57.080 --> 00:55:01.810
That is like, all right, you know
what we're going to do in 1960?

00:55:01.810 --> 00:55:04.670
We're going to go and
talk to Woodrow Wilson.

00:55:04.670 --> 00:55:07.250
And we're going to
make the plea to him

00:55:07.250 --> 00:55:11.850
to make a public statement
condemning lynching, right?

00:55:11.850 --> 00:55:14.650
And also, you know, what's
going on in the background here,

00:55:14.650 --> 00:55:18.210
of course for those who know
a little bit around African,

00:55:18.210 --> 00:55:22.250
Americans, relationship,
Wilson, you guys are like,

00:55:22.250 --> 00:55:25.360
that's been [inaudible], right?

00:55:25.360 --> 00:55:30.390
Okay. So, Dubois and NAACP actually
come out to support his first term,

00:55:30.390 --> 00:55:33.960 position:56%
in part because he -- Wilson lobbies
African American organizations,

00:55:33.960 --> 00:55:35.670
some people don't know that.

00:55:35.670 --> 00:55:40.450
And so Dubois wrote -- has written
this now, historians like to fight

00:55:40.450 --> 00:55:42.570
about it, this editorial
called Closing Ranks,

00:55:42.570 --> 00:55:45.080 position:56%
which is basically the argument that
African Americans should close ranks

00:55:45.080 --> 00:55:49.600
and support Wilson and that --
and that serving is perhaps a way

00:55:49.600 --> 00:55:53.210
to greater sense of kind of
citizenship in this country.

00:55:53.210 --> 00:55:56.300
But then obviously what
happens is that, right,

00:55:56.300 --> 00:55:59.970
the civil service gets segregated
and African Americans it seems

00:55:59.970 --> 00:56:02.650
like progress is rolled
back, and the NAACP

00:56:02.650 --> 00:56:08.160 position:56%
and all these other civil rights
organizations are upset with Wilson.

00:56:08.160 --> 00:56:10.570
The second term though, what I
found fascinating is the NAACP just

00:56:10.570 --> 00:56:15.980
doesn't stop their relentless like
kind persistence around Wilson.

00:56:15.980 --> 00:56:20.640
In the second term, while he
is still the staunch southern

00:56:20.640 --> 00:56:25.730
segregationist, and not by any
means great on matters of race,

00:56:25.730 --> 00:56:29.130
there is a softening in Wilson's
racial tone towards African

00:56:29.130 --> 00:56:32.750
Americans in his second term
that I found interesting,

00:56:32.750 --> 00:56:36.230
a tiny bit confusing, but
interesting nonetheless.

00:56:36.230 --> 00:56:37.530
And so there's two
very quick things.

00:56:37.530 --> 00:56:39.910
I know I'm like on two
minutes, Mary, I'm sorry.

00:56:39.910 --> 00:56:42.530
So two big things for me that I --

00:56:42.530 --> 00:56:46.850
that I highlight that I think are
worth making mention of in terms

00:56:46.850 --> 00:56:50.390
of -- because at the end of
the day my work and my concern,

00:56:50.390 --> 00:56:53.870
at least in the academy, is the
impact that social movement actors,

00:56:53.870 --> 00:56:58.530
specifically black and brown
social movement actors can have

00:56:58.530 --> 00:57:00.600
on pushing the boundaries
of the American state

00:57:00.600 --> 00:57:03.200
and American institutions
in new directions.

00:57:03.200 --> 00:57:05.640
So the -- there's this
horrible race massacre

00:57:05.640 --> 00:57:07.760
that happens in East St. Louis.

00:57:07.760 --> 00:57:13.430
And it is -- it results because
of labor tensions as a result

00:57:13.430 --> 00:57:17.540
of the draft and also
of the great migration,

00:57:17.540 --> 00:57:21.120
and they are resenting this new
African American presence in town.

00:57:21.120 --> 00:57:24.850
And so what happens one day that
sets this off is they then go --

00:57:24.850 --> 00:57:26.600
the whites in Phil -- not in
Philip's [assumed spelling] County,

00:57:26.600 --> 00:57:29.880
excuse me, in East St. Louis, go
to the African American section

00:57:29.880 --> 00:57:32.290
of town, light houses on fire.

00:57:32.290 --> 00:57:36.900
So it was either stay inside and
burn alive or face a firing squad

00:57:36.900 --> 00:57:38.510
as you ran out of the house, right?

00:57:38.510 --> 00:57:42.060
And so 1000's of men, women, and
children died in East St. Louis.

00:57:42.060 --> 00:57:44.750
It's a horrible massacre.

00:57:44.750 --> 00:57:48.610
So what the NAACP did to organize
is they launched at that time,

00:57:48.610 --> 00:57:52.150
to that point, was the biggest
demonstration of African Americans

00:57:52.150 --> 00:57:57.220
in history in July of 1917, don't
5th Avenue in New York City,

00:57:57.220 --> 00:58:00.640
10,000 African Americans
marched silently down 5th Ave.

00:58:00.640 --> 00:58:03.740
to protest increasing
violence and the St. --

00:58:03.740 --> 00:58:08.600
the St. Louis massacre,
East St. Louis massacre.

00:58:08.600 --> 00:58:10.600
They then afterwards,
a few days afterwards,

00:58:10.600 --> 00:58:12.550
take a delegation to Wilson.

00:58:12.550 --> 00:58:15.170
Joseph Tumulty, his personal
secretary, meets them at --

00:58:15.170 --> 00:58:16.650
meet them, provides buffering.

00:58:16.650 --> 00:58:19.530
Is like, hey, hey, hey,
you can't talk to Wilson.

00:58:19.530 --> 00:58:21.100
He doesn't want to talk to you.

00:58:21.100 --> 00:58:23.920
In this really weird exchange,

00:58:23.920 --> 00:58:27.520
Wilson then sends the following day
Tumulty a letter that is like --

00:58:27.520 --> 00:58:31.240 position:56%
that says, I would like to meet with
the delegation if it's possible.

00:58:31.240 --> 00:58:33.850
And Tumulty is like, I've
already contacted a governor

00:58:33.850 --> 00:58:35.420
to try to run interference.

00:58:35.420 --> 00:58:36.720
You don't need to meet with them.

00:58:36.720 --> 00:58:40.090
And Wilson says, no, I actually
think I do need to meet with them.

00:58:40.090 --> 00:58:43.950
And so he sits down, and this is in
James Wood Johnson's autobiography,

00:58:43.950 --> 00:58:47.070
he sits down and have a long
conversation and they tell him,

00:58:47.070 --> 00:58:50.410
at least James -- according to
James Wood Johnson's account,

00:58:50.410 --> 00:58:52.420 position:56%
they tell him about racial violence.

00:58:52.420 --> 00:58:56.000
They ask him to make a
statement condemning lynching,

00:58:56.000 --> 00:58:58.650
and he actually does.

00:58:58.650 --> 00:59:00.430
Two months later he
makes a statement

00:59:00.430 --> 00:59:03.100
to Congress condemning lynching.

00:59:03.100 --> 00:59:07.300
And in closing I think it's
important and are useful to think

00:59:07.300 --> 00:59:11.030
about in times of resistant
president the impact

00:59:11.030 --> 00:59:15.130
that social movement actors,
even though kind of marginalize,

00:59:15.130 --> 00:59:18.600
might have on a president
and also on a nation.

00:59:18.600 --> 00:59:20.510
Thanks a lot.

00:59:20.510 --> 00:59:25.500
