00:59:32.580 --> 00:59:35.510
&gt;&gt; David Rabban: So first I just
wanted to echo previous thanks

00:59:35.510 --> 00:59:38.240
to Ryan Reft and to the
Library of Congress,

00:59:38.240 --> 00:59:43.580
to which I'm almost greatly
indebted for my -- for my research.

00:59:43.580 --> 00:59:46.520
And also thank the --

00:59:46.520 --> 00:59:51.720
my co-panelists, who have
given just a fabulous, I think,

00:59:51.720 --> 00:59:56.210
panoply of views on World
War I, particularly to Megan,

00:59:56.210 --> 00:59:58.600
who I think has [inaudible]
up what I want

00:59:58.600 --> 01:00:00.970
to briefly address very nicely.

01:00:00.970 --> 01:00:05.150
And that is that we generally
associate World War I,

01:00:05.150 --> 01:00:11.670
and war more generally, across
history with, on the one hand,

01:00:11.670 --> 01:00:18.550
the expansion of state capacity,
the development of new forms

01:00:18.550 --> 01:00:26.510 position:56%
of governance, and new fiscal power,
the provision of social services,

01:00:26.510 --> 01:00:29.060
the rationalization of industry.

01:00:29.060 --> 01:00:32.480
And we often -- we often
associate that aspect of war making

01:00:32.480 --> 01:00:35.780
on the home front and we
see it in a positive way,

01:00:35.780 --> 01:00:40.610
that that kind state building
is actually a beneficial effect

01:00:40.610 --> 01:00:42.100
of many major wars.

01:00:42.100 --> 01:00:47.090 position:56%
On the other hand, we all recognize,
and Geoff and David have spoken

01:00:47.090 --> 01:00:52.490
to it very eloquently,
that war tends to lead

01:00:52.490 --> 01:00:57.740
to massive state repression
of dissent in particular,

01:00:57.740 --> 01:01:01.850
but often maybe of a variety
of vulnerable social groups.

01:01:01.850 --> 01:01:06.530
So on one hand, we kind of
like the sort of expansions

01:01:06.530 --> 01:01:10.280
and transformations of the national
state that we get in wartime.

01:01:10.280 --> 01:01:12.410
On the other hand, it
seems to come along

01:01:12.410 --> 01:01:18.200
with some pretty bad,
negative effects.

01:01:18.200 --> 01:01:21.300
And what I want to
highlight is actually,

01:01:21.300 --> 01:01:24.710
there's kind of some overlap
and some contradiction

01:01:24.710 --> 01:01:29.230
between these two features
of what happens

01:01:29.230 --> 01:01:31.730
on the home front during
World War I,

01:01:31.730 --> 01:01:35.210
and I think many American
wars thereafter.

01:01:35.210 --> 01:01:39.440
And that is that, a third thing
that goes on during World War I,

01:01:39.440 --> 01:01:43.190
and that would continue to go on --

01:01:43.190 --> 01:01:48.640 position:56%
be repeated and really intensified
during World War II in some spheres,

01:01:48.640 --> 01:01:52.130
is a growth and a form
of state capacity

01:01:52.130 --> 01:01:55.830
that I don't think we usually
think of a form of state capacity,

01:01:55.830 --> 01:01:59.980
and that is the provision
of civil libertarian rights.

01:01:59.980 --> 01:02:04.020
That actually there
are many examples

01:02:04.020 --> 01:02:08.300
of the executive branch
during World War I,

01:02:08.300 --> 01:02:11.470
of wartime administrators trying

01:02:11.470 --> 01:02:15.740
to either create new
civil libertarian rights

01:02:15.740 --> 01:02:19.100
or expand the reach of
recognized preexisting civil

01:02:19.100 --> 01:02:20.400
libertarian rights.

01:02:20.400 --> 01:02:24.820
And so I want to jut briefly run
through four examples of this

01:02:24.820 --> 01:02:32.890 position:56%
and then close by what I think these
examples do and do not show us.

01:02:32.890 --> 01:02:35.780
So the first example
is the War Department,

01:02:35.780 --> 01:02:38.600
and Ryan nicely referenced
in his introduction.

01:02:38.600 --> 01:02:41.480
So in the War Department,
which was responsible not just

01:02:41.480 --> 01:02:45.480 position:56%
for fighting the war but for running
the draft during World War I,

01:02:45.480 --> 01:02:48.400
the War Department was
run by Newton Baker,

01:02:48.400 --> 01:02:51.720
an avowed pacifist,
prior to World War I.

01:02:51.720 --> 01:02:55.670
And his second-in-command was
Frederick Keppel, the former dean

01:02:55.670 --> 01:02:57.120
of Columbia University,

01:02:57.120 --> 01:03:00.210
also an avowed pacifist
prior to World War I.

01:03:00.210 --> 01:03:02.500
And they staffed up War
Department with a number

01:03:02.500 --> 01:03:09.230
of young progressive
lawyers and intellectuals.

01:03:09.230 --> 01:03:11.930
Foremost most among
them, for my purposes,

01:03:11.930 --> 01:03:14.430
the young Harvard law
professor Felix Frankfurter,

01:03:14.430 --> 01:03:18.010
who was very involved in the
creation of the new republic

01:03:18.010 --> 01:03:21.840
and was a leading progressive mind,

01:03:21.840 --> 01:03:25.400
and would go on to
be one for some time.

01:03:25.400 --> 01:03:28.440
Felix Frankfurter was an
assistant in the War Department

01:03:28.440 --> 01:03:32.010
and he was tasked with
figuring out what to do

01:03:32.010 --> 01:03:34.210
about conscientious objection.

01:03:34.210 --> 01:03:37.960
What to do with the problem
of folks who got drafted,

01:03:37.960 --> 01:03:42.200
but because they were
pacifists didn't want to fight.

01:03:42.200 --> 01:03:48.250
The Selective Service Act of
1917 had a very narrow provision

01:03:48.250 --> 01:03:49.750
for conscientious objection.

01:03:49.750 --> 01:03:52.180
It basically said that
if you were a member

01:03:52.180 --> 01:03:55.860
of a well-recognized
pacifist church,

01:03:55.860 --> 01:03:59.610
a formally organized pacifist
church, you could perform

01:03:59.610 --> 01:04:02.830
in uniform noncombat
duty in the army.

01:04:02.830 --> 01:04:08.110
And that was the extent of the
right of conscientious objection.

01:04:08.110 --> 01:04:10.450
Felix Frankfurter, in his mid-30's,

01:04:10.450 --> 01:04:14.140
comes into the War Department
and says, this won't do.

01:04:14.140 --> 01:04:17.120
He's in contact with a lot
of social movement activists

01:04:17.120 --> 01:04:21.120
on the civil libertarian side
of things and the pacifist side

01:04:21.120 --> 01:04:23.750
of things, and basically
creates a blueprint

01:04:23.750 --> 01:04:26.420
for an entirely different
administration

01:04:26.420 --> 01:04:29.470
of conscientious objection during
World War I, a blueprint that goes

01:04:29.470 --> 01:04:33.270
on to be implemented,
imperfectly but in a --

01:04:33.270 --> 01:04:37.330
in a very different way than what
Congress had actually imagined.

01:04:37.330 --> 01:04:40.250
Frankfurter says that right of
conscientious objection needs

01:04:40.250 --> 01:04:47.060
to be expanded to pacifists who are
not members of official churches,

01:04:47.060 --> 01:04:53.710
pacifists or otherwise, and needs
to be extended even to pacifists

01:04:53.710 --> 01:04:59.450
who do not have religious grounds
for their objections to war.

01:04:59.450 --> 01:05:04.820
And finally, he argues
that pacifists need

01:05:04.820 --> 01:05:09.820 position:56%
to be offered alternative civilian
service, non-uniform service outside

01:05:09.820 --> 01:05:12.980
of the military during the war.

01:05:12.980 --> 01:05:16.410
And his fourth suggestion
is that this expanded right

01:05:16.410 --> 01:05:19.090
of conscientious objection
needs to be implemented not

01:05:19.090 --> 01:05:23.470
by local draft boards, which
were constituted by volunteers

01:05:23.470 --> 01:05:29.640
from the community, but by a
centralized committee of sort

01:05:29.640 --> 01:05:32.460 position:56%
of nationally respected legal minds.

01:05:32.460 --> 01:05:34.290
All of those things happen.

01:05:34.290 --> 01:05:39.420
A Board of Inquiry was
established, headed by the dean

01:05:39.420 --> 01:05:43.080 position:56%
of Columbia Law School, Harlan Fiske
Stone, who like Frankfurter will go

01:05:43.080 --> 01:05:44.980
on to be a Justice
of the Supreme Court.

01:05:44.980 --> 01:05:47.860
And they basically take
all of the -- they go --

01:05:47.860 --> 01:05:51.080
they find where all of
the alleged pacifists are,

01:05:51.080 --> 01:05:52.860
all of those who have
not [inaudible] the right

01:05:52.860 --> 01:05:55.770
of conscientious objection are
being mistreated in the army camps,

01:05:55.770 --> 01:05:57.990
they basically hold a kind of --

01:05:57.990 --> 01:06:01.120
this ad hoc form of
administrative adjudication

01:06:01.120 --> 01:06:05.400
and they get those pacifists into
alternative civilian service.

01:06:05.400 --> 01:06:09.370
Okay, Frankfurter then, right after
having written that blueprint,

01:06:09.370 --> 01:06:13.890
goes on and is appointed to Woodrow
Wilson's mediation commission

01:06:13.890 --> 01:06:18.110
in 1917, which was having to
deal with the massive problem

01:06:18.110 --> 01:06:23.270
of labor unrest at the
beginning of World War I.

01:06:23.270 --> 01:06:25.850
While on the mediation commission
Frankfurter writes another

01:06:25.850 --> 01:06:31.060
blueprint, which is a blueprint
for a more powerful board,

01:06:31.060 --> 01:06:32.800
national administration board,

01:06:32.800 --> 01:06:35.830
that will basically have
primary jurisdiction

01:06:35.830 --> 01:06:39.420
over labor disputes during the war.

01:06:39.420 --> 01:06:42.600
That leads to the creation of the
National War Labor Board headed

01:06:42.600 --> 01:06:45.190
by former president Taft.

01:06:45.190 --> 01:06:49.280
And the National War
Labor Board in the --

01:06:49.280 --> 01:06:52.820
as the labor historian
Joseph McCartin has shown,

01:06:52.820 --> 01:06:58.280
what it basically does is it
creates a massive incentive

01:06:58.280 --> 01:07:02.780 position:56%
for nonunionized workers, especially
in industries that are vital

01:07:02.780 --> 01:07:05.640
to the war effort, to strike.

01:07:05.640 --> 01:07:08.710
Because the only way the
National War Labor Board can come

01:07:08.710 --> 01:07:12.600
in to mediate a labor dispute
is if there is a labor dispute

01:07:12.600 --> 01:07:14.550
or a pending labor dispute.

01:07:14.550 --> 01:07:19.460
And so there is a massive
strike wave that actually --

01:07:19.460 --> 01:07:20.790
there's a first strike
wave in early --

01:07:20.790 --> 01:07:24.960
in mid-'17, and then in 1918
there's a massive strike wave --

01:07:24.960 --> 01:07:29.440
a second massive strike wave once
the -- these workers realized that,

01:07:29.440 --> 01:07:32.670
oh, if we threatened to strike
or strike we'll get mediation

01:07:32.670 --> 01:07:34.270
from the National War Labor Board.

01:07:34.270 --> 01:07:42.100
They do -- over a million Americans
join unions during the war.

01:07:42.100 --> 01:07:44.840
So it's massive -- and particularly

01:07:44.840 --> 01:07:48.490
in the previously nonunionized
industrial --

01:07:48.490 --> 01:07:51.070
many nonunionized industrial
sectors.

01:07:51.070 --> 01:07:55.640
So here we see a massive
expansion of Freedom of Association

01:07:55.640 --> 01:07:57.920
and what legal historian
[inaudible],

01:07:57.920 --> 01:08:00.900
a colleague of Geoff Stones,
has called the right to agitate

01:08:00.900 --> 01:08:03.310
in the early 20th century.

01:08:03.310 --> 01:08:07.080
Third and fourth examples
are pretty quick.

01:08:07.080 --> 01:08:14.000
The third example is a
less -- a less happy story,

01:08:14.000 --> 01:08:17.750
and it's one that actually
Geoff has brilliantly laid

01:08:17.750 --> 01:08:21.240
out in Perilous Times, and that
is the work by some members

01:08:21.240 --> 01:08:23.730
of the Justice Department
during World War I to try

01:08:23.730 --> 01:08:29.290 position:56%
to mitigate the degree of repression
of antiwar dissenter in the war.

01:08:29.290 --> 01:08:32.990
This is John Lord O'Brian, who
headed the war emergency division

01:08:32.990 --> 01:08:35.910
of the Justice Department,
and along with Alfred Bettman.

01:08:35.910 --> 01:08:42.080 position:56%
As Geoff has shown, they -- although
certainly did a lot of prosecution

01:08:42.080 --> 01:08:48.340
of wartime dissent, they really did
hold to a narrower interpretation

01:08:48.340 --> 01:08:50.660
of the Espionage Act than the one

01:08:50.660 --> 01:08:52.700
that was often implemented
by the courts.

01:08:52.700 --> 01:08:57.140
They also tried to resist the
Postmaster General, who was engaged

01:08:57.140 --> 01:08:59.210
in massive censorship at the time.

01:08:59.210 --> 01:09:03.940
These efforts were not terribly
successful, interestingly,

01:09:03.940 --> 01:09:06.570
and this will be one of my
takeaways, as Geoff shows,

01:09:06.570 --> 01:09:11.190
in large part because
the Justice Department

01:09:11.190 --> 01:09:13.360
at the time was actually
quite decentralized.

01:09:13.360 --> 01:09:16.560
So even though John Lord O'Brian
and Alfred Bettman had these views,

01:09:16.560 --> 01:09:21.590
district U.S. attorneys did not,
they were bringing the cases.

01:09:21.590 --> 01:09:24.600
And then another form of
decentralization was the jury.

01:09:24.600 --> 01:09:28.320
These cases went to juries, and
even despite the formal views

01:09:28.320 --> 01:09:31.570
of the heads of the DOJ about
what the Espionage Act entailed,

01:09:31.570 --> 01:09:37.810
juries would implement a much more
aggressive interpretation leading

01:09:37.810 --> 01:09:41.950
to many of the prosecutions
that Geoff did -

01:09:41.950 --> 01:09:45.110
convictions that Geoff
and David talked about.

01:09:45.110 --> 01:09:49.610
Finally, the Bureau of Immigration,
Louis Post, the assistant secretary

01:09:49.610 --> 01:09:53.500
of labor, who was in charge at
the Bureau of Immigration during

01:09:53.500 --> 01:09:56.710
and immediately after World War I,

01:09:56.710 --> 01:10:01.560
pushed back against then Attorney
General Mitchell Palmer's famous

01:10:01.560 --> 01:10:02.860
Red Raid.

01:10:02.860 --> 01:10:05.300
So this is the Red Scare that
immediately follows World War I,

01:10:05.300 --> 01:10:11.660
leads to 1000's of attempted
deportations of supposed radicals.

01:10:11.660 --> 01:10:18.540
Louis Post cancels over 1500 of
these -- of these deportations,

01:10:18.540 --> 01:10:22.650
sort of trying to vindicate to
some extent the rights of freedom

01:10:22.650 --> 01:10:25.400
of association and
freedom of speech of --

01:10:25.400 --> 01:10:28.410
even of immigrants and
even of non-citizens.

01:10:28.410 --> 01:10:30.750
Okay, so what to take from this?

01:10:30.750 --> 01:10:32.190
What to take from this idea

01:10:32.190 --> 01:10:36.980
that actually during World War
I the state doesn't just repress

01:10:36.980 --> 01:10:38.350
or violate civil liberties,

01:10:38.350 --> 01:10:44.140
but actually supplies new civil
libertarian rights, or new vehicles

01:10:44.140 --> 01:10:46.290
for vindicating civil
libertarian rights.

01:10:46.290 --> 01:10:48.780
I tell this story not to kind of --

01:10:48.780 --> 01:10:51.770
not in an effort to
mitigate the story

01:10:51.770 --> 01:10:57.030
of repression -- I'm out of time?

01:10:57.030 --> 01:10:58.330
Okay, one more minute.

01:10:58.330 --> 01:11:02.970
Thanks. Not to mitigate the
stories of repression of that Geoff

01:11:02.970 --> 01:11:06.810
and David have laid out
and that we know so well,

01:11:06.810 --> 01:11:10.110
and it wasn't just these
Espionage Act cases.

01:11:10.110 --> 01:11:13.890 position:56%
There's massive racial violence that
continues throughout World War I,

01:11:13.890 --> 01:11:16.470 position:56%
massive violence against immigrants.

01:11:16.470 --> 01:11:20.460
So goal is not to say, yeah, you
know, America did some bad things,

01:11:20.460 --> 01:11:22.230
but they also did some good things.

01:11:22.230 --> 01:11:25.520
Rather, I think the importance
of recognizing this side

01:11:25.520 --> 01:11:29.010
of the wartime civil liberty
story is to help us think

01:11:29.010 --> 01:11:32.200
about civil liberties
just differently.

01:11:32.200 --> 01:11:35.610
That civil libertarian
rights are not these kind

01:11:35.610 --> 01:11:40.040
of transcendental rights that
emerge from civil society

01:11:40.040 --> 01:11:43.190
that are then used to push
back against state power,

01:11:43.190 --> 01:11:48.020
but historically have generally
been developed inside the state

01:11:48.020 --> 01:11:51.810
by relatively powerful
administrative actors

01:11:51.810 --> 01:11:55.810
that are then supplied
to society to use.

01:11:55.810 --> 01:11:58.980
So that would be, I think, the
point -- the first takeaway.

01:11:58.980 --> 01:12:02.660
The second takeaway, which is
quite related, is that not only;

01:12:02.660 --> 01:12:08.250
therefore, do -- we to some
extent kind of are stuck depending

01:12:08.250 --> 01:12:11.430
on a powerful state to provide
civil libertarian rights.

01:12:11.430 --> 01:12:15.500
As several of these example show,
centralization, which is often seen

01:12:15.500 --> 01:12:18.540
as one the dangers of
wartime administration,

01:12:18.540 --> 01:12:21.980
is actually generally
pro-civil libertarian.

01:12:21.980 --> 01:12:24.430
That in many of these --
in many of these instances,

01:12:24.430 --> 01:12:27.360
so in the War Department --
in the conscription case,

01:12:27.360 --> 01:12:31.680
the War Department administrators
and the National Board

01:12:31.680 --> 01:12:33.580
of Inquiry that's established,

01:12:33.580 --> 01:12:35.940
are all for a much
broader conscientious --

01:12:35.940 --> 01:12:38.250
right of conscientious objection.

01:12:38.250 --> 01:12:39.950
The local draft boards and many

01:12:39.950 --> 01:12:43.510
of the local army training camp
commanders are not, and that leads

01:12:43.510 --> 01:12:45.050
to the difficulties

01:12:45.050 --> 01:12:47.680
in administrating this more
civil libertarian approach.

01:12:47.680 --> 01:12:50.490
Similarly, the DOJ, I
have mentioned the juries

01:12:50.490 --> 01:12:55.660
and the local U.S.
attorneys, similar issue.

01:12:55.660 --> 01:12:57.750
So centralization actually tends

01:12:57.750 --> 01:13:03.860
to help the state promote
these civil libertarian norms.

01:13:03.860 --> 01:13:07.960
And I'll wrap up there.

01:13:07.960 --> 01:13:09.820
I'm happy to -- I think
-- I think --

01:13:09.820 --> 01:13:14.170
I just would want to say that what
happens during World War I isn't

01:13:14.170 --> 01:13:16.400
just kind of, what?

01:13:16.400 --> 01:13:20.490
These efforts to create new
civil libertarian rights provided

01:13:20.490 --> 01:13:21.960
by administrative agencies

01:13:21.960 --> 01:13:26.280
within the national government will
continue and will really, I think,

01:13:26.280 --> 01:13:32.530
be the fundamental institutional
precursor to a lot of new deal

01:13:32.530 --> 01:13:36.460
and World War II agencies that we
then come to associate more readily

01:13:36.460 --> 01:13:38.070
with civil liberties
and civil rights.

01:13:38.070 --> 01:13:39.870
Thanks very much.

