causal engine here?

01:14:33.990 --> 01:14:37.750
Because sometimes it sounds
like Felix Frankfurter was

01:14:37.750 --> 01:14:39.700
in the right place at
the right time, right?

01:14:39.700 --> 01:14:43.540
Or some other character in
history so that the history is sort

01:14:43.540 --> 01:14:47.560
of being driven by, you
know, individual agency

01:14:47.560 --> 01:14:52.270
and the happenstance of the --
of certain people being together.

01:14:52.270 --> 01:14:58.840
Other times, wartime is this
sort of roping causal factor.

01:14:58.840 --> 01:15:04.800
And so to the extent it's the war
that's causing what's happening

01:15:04.800 --> 01:15:08.360
in these stories, what's
exactly the mechanism by that,

01:15:08.360 --> 01:15:11.980
like what about the war,
the war as a set of --

01:15:11.980 --> 01:15:14.080
generating a set of ideas,

01:15:14.080 --> 01:15:16.870
the war generating a set
of institutions, right?

01:15:16.870 --> 01:15:20.360
So if we think about World
War I causing certain things

01:15:20.360 --> 01:15:22.940
in domestic politics and
culture, what's the --

01:15:22.940 --> 01:15:29.550
what's actually the trail
there from this fighting war

01:15:29.550 --> 01:15:32.990
and what we're seeing at home?

01:15:32.990 --> 01:15:34.290
Anybody?

01:15:34.290 --> 01:15:36.580
&gt;&gt; Geoffrey Stone: So in terms
of my particular interest,

01:15:36.580 --> 01:15:38.560
it would seem fairly obvious

01:15:38.560 --> 01:15:44.640
that when a nation is
it war it wants unity.

01:15:44.640 --> 01:15:47.730
Unity is seen as, and
understandably seen,

01:15:47.730 --> 01:15:50.750
as critical to being able to win.

01:15:50.750 --> 01:15:55.720
And once you've decided to enter
a war, winning is critical.

01:15:55.720 --> 01:16:00.490
And so that becomes
the paramount goal.

01:16:00.490 --> 01:16:02.410
And the question is, well,
how do you achieve that?

01:16:02.410 --> 01:16:05.720
Well, one way it's been
understood you achieve that is

01:16:05.720 --> 01:16:10.390
by not creating dissension,
not causing situations

01:16:10.390 --> 01:16:13.110
where people doubt
whether this is worthwhile.

01:16:13.110 --> 01:16:15.440
It's true that if they
doubt that they will go

01:16:15.440 --> 01:16:19.580
to Canada rather than
to go to Vietnam.

01:16:19.580 --> 01:16:24.320 position:56%
Or they will not buy war bonds, or
they will be subordinated if they're

01:16:24.320 --> 01:16:25.620
in the military all ready.

01:16:25.620 --> 01:16:29.640
And all of that has the effect
of dampening the probability

01:16:29.640 --> 01:16:31.490
of being successful in war.

01:16:31.490 --> 01:16:35.260
And assuming you believe
that putting our welfare,

01:16:35.260 --> 01:16:39.000
our lives at stake is
the right thing to do,

01:16:39.000 --> 01:16:41.180
then you've got to be all in.

01:16:41.180 --> 01:16:43.440
And I think that much
of the causality

01:16:43.440 --> 01:16:46.210
of what happens during wartime
is the product of the sense

01:16:46.210 --> 01:16:50.590 position:56%
that if we're going to put
American lives at risk by the 1000's

01:16:50.590 --> 01:16:56.030
or millions, and America's wealth
at risk, and freedom ultimately

01:16:56.030 --> 01:16:58.920
at risk, then we have to be willing
to sacrifice almost everything.

01:16:58.920 --> 01:17:02.370
And that's what Wilson was sort of
saying when he was first advocating

01:17:02.370 --> 01:17:05.740
for his version of the Espionage
Act, which is that, you know,

01:17:05.740 --> 01:17:07.680
everything has to be
put in place so we win.

01:17:07.680 --> 01:17:09.230
That's the only thing that matters.

01:17:09.230 --> 01:17:11.620
Nothing else makes any difference.

01:17:11.620 --> 01:17:16.000
&gt;&gt; Jeremy Kessler: So I want
to emphasize how much war

01:17:16.000 --> 01:17:20.160
at first did not change
the legal tradition, okay.

01:17:20.160 --> 01:17:24.710
You know, the traditional
understanding was we had this great

01:17:24.710 --> 01:17:28.640
theoretical tradition of freedom
of expression in the United States,

01:17:28.640 --> 01:17:34.100
but not much occasion to
invoke it until World War I,

01:17:34.100 --> 01:17:40.270
our first world war where the
country went crazy and overreacted

01:17:40.270 --> 01:17:44.250
and repressed civil liberties,
unprecedented in American history,

01:17:44.250 --> 01:17:46.560
against which there was
an ultimate reaction

01:17:46.560 --> 01:17:49.410
in favor of civil liberties.

01:17:49.410 --> 01:17:53.140
As I, to my surprise,
discovered, right,

01:17:53.140 --> 01:17:57.570
at least the judicial
tradition was extremely hostile

01:17:57.570 --> 01:18:03.990
to all free speech claims of every
[inaudible] imaginable throughout

01:18:03.990 --> 01:18:05.670
the 19th century.

01:18:05.670 --> 01:18:09.750
And World War I only
extended that tradition.

01:18:09.750 --> 01:18:15.490
It didn't change it at first,
but war as causal agent.

01:18:15.490 --> 01:18:18.470
I think many Americans
during the war

01:18:18.470 --> 01:18:22.980
for the first time
realized the consequences

01:18:22.980 --> 01:18:28.300
of this long-term repressive,
I would say, tradition.

01:18:28.300 --> 01:18:33.630
And also, Roger Baldwin
himself, the founder of the ACLU,

01:18:33.630 --> 01:18:36.380
many others, do we change?

01:18:36.380 --> 01:18:41.440
People for the first time started
thinking about the consequences

01:18:41.440 --> 01:18:45.740
of this tradition and worried
about it and decided we need

01:18:45.740 --> 01:18:49.110
to protect political speech more.

01:18:49.110 --> 01:18:54.430
So to a great extent, I think,
World War I transformed the views

01:18:54.430 --> 01:18:58.360
about free speech of many
people who later defended it,

01:18:58.360 --> 01:19:01.530
most obviously the
leaders of the ACLU.

01:19:01.530 --> 01:19:02.990
&gt;&gt; Geoffrey Stone: Can
I add a word to that?

01:19:02.990 --> 01:19:05.590
The transformation of
Oliver Wendell Holmes.

01:19:05.590 --> 01:19:06.890
&gt;&gt; Jeremy Kessler: Yes.

01:19:06.890 --> 01:19:08.190
&gt;&gt; Geoffrey Stone: Is
a critical example.

01:19:08.190 --> 01:19:09.490
&gt;&gt; Jeremy Kessler: Right.

01:19:09.490 --> 01:19:11.950
&gt;&gt; Geoffrey Stone: So as David
said in the first iteration

01:19:11.950 --> 01:19:14.490 position:56%
in which the Supreme Court addressed
the First Amendment question

01:19:14.490 --> 01:19:15.790
about whether these prosecutions

01:19:15.790 --> 01:19:17.890
under the Espionage Act
were constitutional,

01:19:17.890 --> 01:19:19.190
Holmes wrote these opinions,

01:19:19.190 --> 01:19:23.730
basically adopted the bad tendency
test, and affirmed the convictions

01:19:23.730 --> 01:19:26.520
without really writing a
serious opinion at all.

01:19:26.520 --> 01:19:30.320
And then over that next
summer he spent time thinking

01:19:30.320 --> 01:19:33.370
about free speech, the war
had ended, talking to people

01:19:33.370 --> 01:19:35.730
who had been critics
of his opinions,

01:19:35.730 --> 01:19:38.250
some academic, some
lower court judges.

01:19:38.250 --> 01:19:40.920
And comes back the following
fall, only a few months later,

01:19:40.920 --> 01:19:43.310
and writes a stirring opinion

01:19:43.310 --> 01:19:45.780
in which he now says you cannot
punish speech unless it creates a

01:19:45.780 --> 01:19:48.430
clear and present danger
of serious harm

01:19:48.430 --> 01:19:52.530
and launches the judicial tradition
of the protection of free speech

01:19:52.530 --> 01:19:55.180
that we now live with today.

01:19:55.180 --> 01:19:58.430
But that was also very much
the product of the fact

01:19:58.430 --> 01:20:01.650
that he did one thing, he
learned from that experience

01:20:01.650 --> 01:20:04.470
in only a few months to
his credit, came around,

01:20:04.470 --> 01:20:07.040
didn't admit he was wrong, of
course, but came around and --

01:20:07.040 --> 01:20:08.340
&gt;&gt; Jeremy Kessler: Which he
never did about anything.

01:20:08.340 --> 01:20:09.830
&gt;&gt; Geoffrey Stone: Right, never
did about anything, right.

01:20:09.830 --> 01:20:12.110 position:56%
Basically maintained all those
earlier decisions [inaudible] right,

01:20:12.110 --> 01:20:14.230
but never explained how they
could possibly be reconciled

01:20:14.230 --> 01:20:15.630
with his new approach.

01:20:15.630 --> 01:20:19.950
But then he became -- he became
really the initial spokesperson

01:20:19.950 --> 01:20:25.680
for the idea of a really robust
meaning of the First Amendment.

01:20:25.680 --> 01:20:27.740
&gt;&gt; Megan Ming Francis: In terms
of what war does, I think for me

01:20:27.740 --> 01:20:29.040
and thinking about the NAACP

01:20:29.040 --> 01:20:31.130
or black political
activism during this time,

01:20:31.130 --> 01:20:33.600
I think it made them
reevaluate what was meant

01:20:33.600 --> 01:20:35.150
by citizenship in this
country, right?

01:20:35.150 --> 01:20:37.790
And I kind of -- these treasured
American ideals, such as freedom

01:20:37.790 --> 01:20:42.800
and democracy, especially for those
who had volunteered for these kind

01:20:42.800 --> 01:20:45.820
like separated camps for
training and those who had gone

01:20:45.820 --> 01:20:47.550
and also come back, right?

01:20:47.550 --> 01:20:51.510
And I think especially for
those who served and came back

01:20:51.510 --> 01:20:54.050
and the violence that
occurred to them,

01:20:54.050 --> 01:20:56.880
and so I think one the well-known
examples is the African American

01:20:56.880 --> 01:21:02.690
soldier who's wearing his --
wearing his uniform in the south.

01:21:02.690 --> 01:21:04.320
I forget what city he's in.

01:21:04.320 --> 01:21:07.180
He is then harassed and then
his eyes are gouged out,

01:21:07.180 --> 01:21:09.640
in part because they
find it so offensive

01:21:09.640 --> 01:21:12.350
that this black man could be
wearing the uniform, right?

01:21:12.350 --> 01:21:14.370
And so there's all these
different moments of violence.

01:21:14.370 --> 01:21:18.030
And I think for them it
actually I think fueled them

01:21:18.030 --> 01:21:19.330
to push harder, right?

01:21:19.330 --> 01:21:22.170 position:56%
That if you want us to serve and die

01:21:22.170 --> 01:21:24.900
for this country then you all
got to do some more, right?

01:21:24.900 --> 01:21:27.550
And I think -- I mean,
just to pull a little bit

01:21:27.550 --> 01:21:31.380
on what Geoff was saying here about
Holmes, he's a fascinating justice.

01:21:31.380 --> 01:21:36.930
But I think it wasn't just
for the NAACP and or, right,

01:21:36.930 --> 01:21:38.810
like African Americans,
that kind of --

01:21:38.810 --> 01:21:43.090
that pushed them to reevaluate what
citizenship means in this country,

01:21:43.090 --> 01:21:44.660
but also for political elite.

01:21:44.660 --> 01:21:48.080 position:56%
So one of my favorites Supreme Court
cases is Morvey Dempsey [assumed

01:21:48.080 --> 01:21:52.110
spelling], a case decided by
-- a case decided in 1923.

01:21:52.110 --> 01:21:54.950
Holmes is going to write
the opinion of the court.

01:21:54.950 --> 01:21:57.460
And basically it's a case

01:21:57.460 --> 01:22:00.530
around these 12 African
American men Arkansas,

01:22:00.530 --> 01:22:03.360 position:56%
and which is the first case in which
the federal courts get involved

01:22:03.360 --> 01:22:04.660
in a state criminal court trial.

01:22:04.660 --> 01:22:07.770
And he's like, hey, you know what,
mob dominated trial that kind

01:22:07.770 --> 01:22:09.810
of violate the due
process clause, right.

01:22:09.810 --> 01:22:11.110
I don't know.

01:22:11.110 --> 01:22:13.090
But, and it's an important
-- and it's really important.

01:22:13.090 --> 01:22:15.300
I mean, on previous cases
that Holmes I think had been

01:22:15.300 --> 01:22:17.240
on the right side of history,
but he hadn't been able

01:22:17.240 --> 01:22:19.030
to get his fellow justices
on his side.

01:22:19.030 --> 01:22:21.470
And so this is kind of his
big vindication for him.

01:22:21.470 --> 01:22:24.890
So it's not just, I think, kind
of those on the ground or those

01:22:24.890 --> 01:22:29.300
who were marginalized, I think it's
also those elite, political elites,

01:22:29.300 --> 01:22:33.740
again who are -- who are
reevaluating this notion.

01:22:33.740 --> 01:22:35.400
&gt;&gt; David Rabban: Thanks.

01:22:35.400 --> 01:22:39.460
So how -- yeah, this is like
one of the biggest problems

01:22:39.460 --> 01:22:40.980
that I think I've struggled with.

01:22:40.980 --> 01:22:46.420 position:56%
And I know Mary has -- Mary and many
other legal historians have really

01:22:46.420 --> 01:22:48.090
shed some light on,
how to deal with the --

01:22:48.090 --> 01:22:52.060
what is the causal relationship
between war as this kind

01:22:52.060 --> 01:22:55.900
of an event, a sort of
exogenous shock to the system,

01:22:55.900 --> 01:23:00.380
and then the individual, whether
it be executive official or judge

01:23:00.380 --> 01:23:02.550
or social movement activist?

01:23:02.550 --> 01:23:05.260
I think that one way
of getting at that,

01:23:05.260 --> 01:23:10.700
and it's actually been
suggested in some of David

01:23:10.700 --> 01:23:15.350
and Megan's remarks just now,
is to introduce a third category

01:23:15.350 --> 01:23:22.230 position:56%
between the two, which are
longer-term and long-running social,

01:23:22.230 --> 01:23:24.430
cultural, and economic conflicts

01:23:24.430 --> 01:23:26.960
that predate the war
and that postdate it.

01:23:26.960 --> 01:23:29.540
I think it's really
important to understand

01:23:29.540 --> 01:23:35.050
that war emerges precisely
from the social, cultural,

01:23:35.050 --> 01:23:37.890
and economic conflicts, both
nationally and internationally,

01:23:37.890 --> 01:23:41.950
and that war then does indeed
overdetermine those social,

01:23:41.950 --> 01:23:43.270
cultural, and economic conflicts.

01:23:43.270 --> 01:23:45.380
Now, how does it overdetermine it?

01:23:45.380 --> 01:23:51.380 position:56%
Here I think like I would -- I would
point to Geoff's point about unity.

01:23:51.380 --> 01:23:52.680
So you have a war.

01:23:52.680 --> 01:23:56.220
It's complex and we argue
over why exactly it emerges

01:23:56.220 --> 01:23:57.520
at a particular time.

01:23:57.520 --> 01:24:01.580
But once we decide we're going
to have a war, unit, unity,

01:24:01.580 --> 01:24:05.310
collective sacrifice,
rationalization,

01:24:05.310 --> 01:24:08.610
all of these, this is needed.

01:24:08.610 --> 01:24:13.780
On the one hand that push
for unity will indeed kind

01:24:13.780 --> 01:24:18.530
of sometimes suppress many
of the social, cultural,

01:24:18.530 --> 01:24:21.330
economic actors involved in
the preexisting conflict.

01:24:21.330 --> 01:24:22.630
So on the one hand that search

01:24:22.630 --> 01:24:27.820
for unity will kind
of shutdown conflict.

01:24:27.820 --> 01:24:32.510
But on the other hand, the very
fact that the state needs unity

01:24:32.510 --> 01:24:36.510
to run the war actually
renders it vulnerable,

01:24:36.510 --> 01:24:40.520
and perhaps newly vulnerable to
some of these conflicts and to some

01:24:40.520 --> 01:24:42.480
of these social forces
involved in them.

01:24:42.480 --> 01:24:46.430
So precisely to get the unity
that's needed to fight the war,

01:24:46.430 --> 01:24:52.130
the state needs to begin to try to
conciliate some of the conflicts

01:24:52.130 --> 01:24:56.580
that previously could just burn.

01:24:56.580 --> 01:24:57.920
You know, did not -- did not --

01:24:57.920 --> 01:25:00.310
the state did not necessarily
have an immediate reason to deal

01:25:00.310 --> 01:25:03.080
with some of the conflicts and
with some of the social movements

01:25:03.080 --> 01:25:08.470
or social groups prior to
needing everyone to come together

01:25:08.470 --> 01:25:09.770
to fight the war effectively.

01:25:09.770 --> 01:25:12.650
So that -- I would -- I would
introduce that third category,

01:25:12.650 --> 01:25:16.580
mediating between the individual
and the war event as crucial.

01:25:16.580 --> 01:25:17.910
&gt;&gt; Mary Dudziak: Yeah, this
is interesting and helpful.

01:25:17.910 --> 01:25:20.610
And as you were speaking I was
thinking of, it's Randolph Bourne,

01:25:20.610 --> 01:25:22.670
right, who says, war is
the health of the state.

01:25:22.670 --> 01:25:25.810
And that it's, you know,
in war that people sort

01:25:25.810 --> 01:25:29.690
of see the state, he said.

01:25:29.690 --> 01:25:36.120
And so this sort of connection
between moments when there's a need

01:25:36.120 --> 01:25:40.680
for sort of broad-based support
for a government project,

01:25:40.680 --> 01:25:46.790
which we call war, you know, that's
a point when there are these sort

01:25:46.790 --> 01:25:49.750
of -- as well as sort of the social
and cultural dynamics that come

01:25:49.750 --> 01:25:55.350
out in the First Amendment context,
the importance of, you know,

01:25:55.350 --> 01:25:59.690
forms of state formation and their
relationship to the polity, the war

01:25:59.690 --> 01:26:03.520
and the health -- the health of
the state we're seeing happening.

01:26:03.520 --> 01:26:07.040
I would just say as an aside, that
this idea about the need for unity,

01:26:07.040 --> 01:26:10.660
etcetera, you know, we can
probably be on the same page right

01:26:10.660 --> 01:26:12.740
about through World
War II on that story,

01:26:12.740 --> 01:26:16.140
and then of course American
history starts looking differently,

01:26:16.140 --> 01:26:18.430
lots of ideas about how
and why that happens,

01:26:18.430 --> 01:26:20.600
but really beyond the
scope of the panel.

01:26:20.600 --> 01:26:24.620
Can I just ask a Holmes question,
Holmes and, more broadly,

01:26:24.620 --> 01:26:28.040
thinkers at this time, because
as you're talking about Holmes,

01:26:28.040 --> 01:26:30.570
who is so important on the
Supreme Court at this point,

01:26:30.570 --> 01:26:35.840
and Holmes is one of the many
important, in this period,

01:26:35.840 --> 01:26:38.170
Civil War veterans, right?

01:26:38.170 --> 01:26:44.640
And Holmes, when he was in the
war, talked about it as barbarism.

01:26:44.640 --> 01:26:48.770
You know, and he himself
was injured could have died,

01:26:48.770 --> 01:26:51.790
and really talks about
war as barbarity.

01:26:51.790 --> 01:26:54.110
And then later on, I
think was in a -- in a --

01:26:54.110 --> 01:26:59.490
in a graduation address in
1895, you know basically talks

01:26:59.490 --> 01:27:02.240 position:56%
about how wonderful it is, you know,

01:27:02.240 --> 01:27:06.720
